<HEADLINE>
SHAW PROBLEM OUT OF THE BLUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ As spring training ended, the Los Angeles Dodgers
had concerns about their bullpen, but not their closer.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring situational lefty, yes. Finding innings for the middle
relievers, yes. Jeff Shaw? Certainly not.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Dodgers are facing the very real issue of what to do
with Shaw. And everything, except trotting him out there to close
games, seems to be an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to relive something over and over and over
again,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``It's a problem right
now, and we have to figure out a solution. That's all. We'll have
to figure out a plan to see what to do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation wasn't ideal when Shaw had to wait through two
rain delays Friday before allowing a three-run homer to St. Louis'
Craig Paquette in the 12th inning. That cost the Dodgers the win,
but it's not why the Dodgers are examining the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has blown seven of 19 save chances and confidence, from all
sides, is waning. His confidence, Shaw said, was ``rocked a little,
shaken, but not broken.''
</P>
<P>
   In order for Shaw to get right, he needs to pitch, and the
Dodgers might not be willing to put him in pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's making $5 million this season and is guaranteed $6
million next season, so the Dodgers need to get something out of
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are looking for viable options. Mike Fetters has the
experience, but there's a question of whether his right arm can
handle the daily stress of pitching four times a week. Antonio
Osuna might be the one, but he's caved on that role before; Matt
Herges has the make-up, including an arm that recovers quickly and
the requisite fastball, but he's a 30-year-old rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers thought they had the problem worked out when Shaw
took a week off at the beginning of June, but after four strong
outings he's had problems in the past two.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's right, he's able to locate the ball with the
movement he wants on it, and do that consistently,'' Johnson said.
``When he tries to muscle it to get some movement on it, he doesn't
locate. When you're muscling it, (the slider) is flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for No. 1: F.P. Santangelo started in center field and
batted leadoff for the first time since Todd Hollandsworth returned
from a hamstring injury June 15. Hollandsworth hasn't produced the
way the Dodgers hoped he would.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth is 10 for 36 (.288), but he's walked just once and
his on-base percentage is .297. In addition, Hollandsworth, given a
chance to play regularly since Devon White's injury May 2, is
hitting .249 with five homers and 12 RBI. His on-base percentage is
a dismal .306, and he's batting .143 (6 for 42) with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you use a Hollandsworth, maybe you sacrifice a little
on-base percentage but you're going to get more run production,''
Johnson said. ``Well, he's kind of been in a funk with the
run-producing. He hasn't swung the bat with runners in scoring
position, he's actually swinging it worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
