<HEADLINE>
ANGELS IN DESPERATE NEED OF SHORTSTOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Justin Baughman's arrival in the clubhouse on
Saturday nearly 19 months after a gruesome broken leg threatened to
end his career may serve as an inspiration to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   It also serves as a example of how desperate the Anaheim Angels'
search for a shortstop has become.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman is the latest to be given an opportunity to fill the
hole that was created six weeks ago when Gary DiSarcina was lost
for the season after shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Benji Gil and Kevin Stocker, who was placed on the disabled list
Friday with tendinitis in his left knee, have been given a shot at
the job, but are batting .205 and .184, respectively. Keith Luuloa
was also given a brief audition.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, who was batting .245 with a team-leading 16 stolen
bases at triple-A Edmonton, will split time with Gil, Manager Mike
Scioscia said. He also gives the Angels an option in the No. 2 spot
in the batting order, a need since Adam Kennedy was dropped to the
No. 8 spot earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said that based on club reports, Baughman has made
remarkable progress since spring training, when he was shunted off
to the minor league camp after one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin was so far removed from competition,'' Scioscia said.
``It took him a lot longer than any of thought it would to regain
his form.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman shattered his leg when he collided with an outfielder
on a pop fly during a game in the Mexican League on Nov. 7, 1998.
``I can't even think about it,'' Scioscia said of the injury.
``It's a remarkable story.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, who batted .255 in 63 games with the Angels in 1998
and appeared to be their second baseman of the future, said his
return to big leagues isn't any more meaningful than the first time
he was called up.
</P>
<P>
   Other than aches and pains, his leg is fine. It was the mental
part of the game that was difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had to be perfect,'' he said of spring training.
``I know they didn't have a lot of time to look at people, so I put
a lot of pressure on myself. I felt when I paid my dues, I'd be
back. I knew if they felt I was ready, I'd get an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson out of equation: Jason Dickson won't be part of the
Angels pitching equation for some time after his decision,
announced Friday night, to undergo arthroscopic shoulder surgery
next week. It's the second surgery in on his right shoulder in 15
months.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson, 2-2 with a 6.11 ERA, missed all of last season after
surgery to repair a torn labrum. Tuesday's surgery will determine
the severity of what the team is calling a frayed labrum.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he's convinced that Dickson was healthy at the
start of the year because he was one of the team's best pitchers in
April. When Dickson returns, he may have to reconsider his
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mechanics aren't ideal, but they're not far off,''
Scioscia said. ``He may have to make adjustments in the way he
delivers the ball to take some pressure off his shoulder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
