<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS HOPING TO CLOSE LEDGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY NENA BAKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The Diamondbacks want to shut the only door - albeit, a
back entrance - through which the public can access detailed
information about the team's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Team executives said the Diamondbacks want an exemption from a
contract that requires the privately held Diamondbacks to give the
public a peek at the team's bottom line, debt, cash flow and even
Managing Partner Jerry Colangelo's seven-figure fee.
</P>
<P>
   `We feel we're a private company, and we'd like to keep it that
way,` President Rich Dozer said.
</P>
<P>
   The financial disclosure contract was intended for the benefit
of bond investors, who helped the Diamondbacks gain more favorable
terms on the repayment of the team's portion of Bank One Ballpark
construction debt.
</P>
<P>
   It requires the team to file financial statements with national
repositories.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also given the public a chance to see how the
Diamondbacks have struggled financially while building a team that
went from worst to first faster than any other in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, when the Diamondbacks rose from the cellar to clinch
the National League West title, the team lost $15.8 million from
operations, compared with an operating profit of $21.1 million a
year earlier, according to the team's unaudited financial
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The team blamed the poor financial performance on the doubling
of player salaries - to $69 million, the ninth-highest in baseball,
combined with stagnating ticket revenues that have continued into
2000.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, June 23, with the Diamondbacks holding a one-game
lead in the NL West, home attendance for the season was down 2
percent from a year earlier to an average of 35,723 per game, the
team said.
</P>
<P>
   The financial disclosure con tract was signed in 1998 when the
team used $126.9 million worth of taxable Phoenix Industrial
Development Authority bonds to refinance its portion of Bank One
Ballpark construction debt .
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers contributed $238 million toward the $355 million
stadium, where the Diamondbacks have a 30-year lease, and the team
put up the rest.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the lease and operating agreements, the team pays the
Maricopa County Stadium District, which owns and operates the
facility, a variety of fees that totaled $2.4 million in 1999,
according to district records.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public-private partnership that built BOB, the team
is not required to file financial information with the stadium
district.
</P>
<P>
   `Our contracts have very difficult escape clauses that make it
prohibitive for the team not to pay, not to produce, to try to
leave,` said Bill Scalzo, stadium district director. `We are
protected very well,` without having to ask for full financial
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Harris, the team's vice president of finance, said the team
is exploring ways in which it can distribute financial information
directly to bondholders instead of through a public repository, as
the contract with bond underwriters now requires.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds are backed by an insurance policy, for which the
Diamondbacks paid a premium, that would cover the bond principal
and interest if the Diamondbacks were not able to make the
payments. That insurance policy also protects the Industrial
Development Authority if the Diamondbacks defaulted, said Bryant
Barber, the authority's bond attorney.
</P>
<P>
   `It's not that we don't care about the Diamondbacks' financial
performance,` Barber said. `It's just that at the end of the day,
the (insurance company) is right there.`
</P>
<P>
   Bondholders - in this case, institutions that can afford to buy
paper that originally sold in $100,000 denominations - are the only
parties that can seek compliance of the financial disclosure
agreement, according to the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Life Insurance Co. of Newport Beach, Calif., which holds
$10 million worth of the bonds, said through a spokeswoman that it
has not been contacted by the Diamondbacks or Bank One, which is
trustee for the bondholders, about a possible exception to the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   `In general, if there is an insurance policy backing (the
bonds), the insurer takes first responsibility for repayment,` said
Pacific Life's Milda Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   That makes financial disclosure by the bond issuer less
critical, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Dozer said he does not expect the team to show an operating
profit in 2000. But he downplayed any potential need for another
infusion from limited partners.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, while in the midst of a cash crunch, the Diamondbacks
called on the team's 29 limited partners, including Phoenix
Newspapers Inc., the parent company of The Arizona Republic, to
kick in an additional $1 million each. Twenty-four investors
complied, including The Republic's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second cash call made on limited partners since the
team began play in 1998. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Nena.Baker(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at (602)
444-8256. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
