<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS END UP ALL WET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson sat in his
office chair, shirt unbuttoned and speaking softly. Players slowly
filtered through an energy-less clubhouse, kicked back in chairs
with heavy eyes and tired minds and bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was all that was needed to understand how the Dodgers
felt after sitting through three rain delays that turned a
high-noon baseball game into one that really didn't get going until
twilight.
</P>
<P>
   That the Dodgers lost 6-1 to St. Louis at Busch Stadium on
Saturday was a small part of it. That three rain delays lasted four
hours, 55 minutes on an afternoon that concluded seven hours, 47
minutes after the scheduled first pitch told the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the adrenaline starts going, you have to shut it down,''
said Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, who's hitting streak
ended at 13 games. ``We had three different times we were going to
start, you get ready to go and they say it's raining again, so you
go back and relax and get your mind off of what's going on. Then,
they say you're going again. That hot-cold stuff, it's hard to get
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than 24 hours in St. Louis, the Dodgers saw more rain
and rain delays than they'll see in a decade in Los Angeles. In
total, the first two games of the series produced five rain delays
lasting five hours, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the more painful number for the Dodgers is two - as in
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a grueling day, and the guys were a little bit worn
down,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``We grinded hard.
We're still grinding, but the tank is a little dry. ... It happens
all the time where you sit around and you play. It was just a
little tougher since it was a long game (Friday) night and you get
up early in the morning for a (12:25 p.m.) game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the rain also complicated the pitching arrangements,
which probably will see Orel Hershiser start Monday, his second in
three days.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (1-4) started against the Cardinals, but that was
after two rain delays. The start of the game was delayed one hour,
6 minutes, and then 33 more minutes after the top of the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one, we really missed our window,'' Hershiser said.
``That radar really screwed us up, I guess. If we had just battled
through that first little downpour, about three minutes or five
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser allowed a 483-foot, two-run homer to Mark McGwire -
the 550th of his career - in the first inning to give the Cardinals
a 2-0 lead. But when the rain came after Eduardo Perez's one-out
double in the second (at 2:31 p.m.), Hershiser didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   The game began three hours, 16 minutes later, thanks to a
colossal gaffe from the grounds crew in taking 14 minutes to get
the tarp on, which included Cardinals manager Tony La Russa lending
a hand. They mismanaged putting the tarp on the field, and the
infield was drenched. They spent nearly two hours redoing the
entire infield in the glow of the sun before the game could
restart.
</P>
<P>
   When it finally began again, Monday's scheduled starter, Carlos
Perez, was on the mound. And he possibly proved that maybe he could
pitch out of the bullpen, throwing 4 innings and allowing one run
on two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a guy who doesn't play every day, and I felt like my bat
was 100 pounds, so I can imagine what the other guys were
feeling,'' Dodgers catcher Paul LoDuca said. ``It's one of those
things, but Carlos came out and he threw awesome. He threw great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
