<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS ON BUMPY ROAD TO PASSENGER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BETTY BEARD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Mesa's Williams Gateway Airport, where thousands of Air
Force pilots earned their wings, is now facing its ultimate test:
shedding the last of its drab military fatigues to become a modern
passenger airport.
</P>
<P>
   An old squadron building is about to be remodeled into a
four-gate passenger terminal, and the weed-strewn road in front of
it is about to be paved and widened, the final steps to opening the
airport to passenger service by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams' ambitious plan to become an East Phoenix Valley
passenger alternative to Phoenix's Sky Harbor International Airport
has run into some serious turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Although airport officials have been talking to airlines for
several years, none has signed up so far, not even little charter
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Director Lynn Kusy says that's because efforts to lure
lucrative passenger service just began in earnest this month and
airlines have been waiting to make sure the terminal became
reality.
</P>
<P>
   `They said, `When you have a firm schedule for a terminal, we'll
start discussions,` Kusy said. `We're hoping to have some charter
planes for the Fiesta Bowl.`
</P>
<P>
   Luring passenger service may not be easy, said Mike Boyd, an
airport and airline consultant in Evergreen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it took two years for MidAmerica Airport, created
from part of Scott Air Force Base near St. Louis, to attract
passenger service. &QL; 
NOT MANY CONVERSIONS
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said there haven't been many conversions from former Air
Force bases to commercial airports.
</P>
<P>
   `You've got to be careful with these things,` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, an Air Force base from 1941 to 1993 and nicknamed
Willie by soldiers who spent time there, trained about a fourth of
the Air Force's pilots in the late 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It was in such bad shape that it has taken six years to get it
ready for passenger service. Runways had to be rebuilt or repaired,
the control tower had to be modernized, and lead paint had to be
removed from a hangar, among other things. The Federal Aviation
Administration just certified it last year.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Gateway Airport is already one of the busiest in the
state, recording 236,000 takeoffs and landings last year, about a
third of what Sky Harbor had. It's used for everything from private
planes to corporate jets to cargo transports and military training.
</P>
<P>
   But to become a reliever to Sky Harbor in a decade or two and to
make enough money to pay back its investors - Mesa, Gilbert, the
Gila River Indian Community and Queen Creek - the airport badly
needs passenger service.
</P>
<P>
   About $33 million has already been spent on the airport, with
much of it coming from federal and state grants, as well as the
owners: Mesa, which owns 78 percent; Gilbert and the Gila River
Indian Community, with 10 percent each, and Queen Creek, with 2
percent. Together, they're contributing about $4.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by Williams' officials says the airport could rake
in about $185 million a year with full passenger service and a
larger terminal in 2020. But if it continued with general aviation
and no passenger service, revenues would only be about $7.6 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials say the most likely airlines it can attract
now are smaller companies providing quick jaunts to places like
Colorado or Palm Springs or bringing winter visitors to the
southeast Phoenix area, what those in the industry call `origin and
destination` service. Officials with America West and Southwest
Airlines said they're happy with Sky Harbor and not likely to set
up service at Williams. &QL; 
RELIEVER PLAN QUESTIONED &QL; 
Boyd questions the long-standing plans to make Williams a reliever
airport to Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   `That's the kind of stuff consultants dream up to get a big
invoice,` he said.
</P>
<P>
   But David Krietor, aviation director with Sky Harbor, is
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   `Sky Harbor and Phoenix have always been supportive of Williams
doing commuter service,` Krietor said. `Since it's in a population
center of about 700,000, we think there may be an opportunity for
established airlines and more likely for entrepreneurial service
companies for folks in the East Phoenix Valley.
</P>
<P>
   `We have not heard of any established carrier that wants to
provide service out of Williams, but the world is an extremely
dynamic and complicated place that changes every day,` he added.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Frank, the new marketing director at Williams, said the
airport has several things going for it.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's near several major employers, notably Motorola and
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   `What airlines want the most are business travelers, which we
are rich in,` Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's close to thousands of air travelers, including the
Valley's thickest concentration of winter visitors.
</P>
<P>
   `We think 25 to 27 percent of Sky Harbor customers live closer
to Williams than Sky Harbor,` Kusy said. &QL; 
EASY FOR EAST VALLEY
</P>
<P>
   East Valley fliers would be thrilled, several travel agents
said.
</P>
<P>
   `It's such a horrible rat race to get from here (Chandler) to
there (Sky Harbor) in the morning, especially in the morning when
you're catching an early flight,` said Jeff Kollman, owner of All
Around Travel in Chandler. Going to Williams, he added, `would be a
piece of cake.`
</P>
<P>
   He and Judy Bernard, an agent with Terra Travel in east Mesa,
said charter flights to places like Las Vegas would be especially
popular.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, parts of the old base have been rebuilt and
landscaped, but other parts remain dumpy. Some unusable splintery
old buildings remain. A large part of the old housing area is
vacant, surrounded by green tumbleweeds. Weeds are taking over
narrow roads.
</P>
<P>
   For all the work and expense that's gone into it, it might seem
like it would be easier to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But Kusy points out that the last airport to be built, Denver
International, cost $4.9 billion and was way over budget and behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   `For the $33 million we spent so far,` he said, `this is a real
bargain.` &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-00 0050EDT &QL; 
