<DOCNO> NYT20000625.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4214 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-WIRELESS-AZR &LR;      06-25 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTENNAS DUEL CABLE FOR INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - For years, US West has dug up streets and Cox
Communications has rebuilt green metal boxes in neighborhoods to
enable systems of copper and cables to deliver high-speed Internet
connections to Phoenix area homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, antennas the shape of a pizza box springing up on Phoenix
area roofs signal that a third communications heavyweight has
entered the broadband Internet fray.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance of Sprint Broadband, available at the moment only
in the Phoenix area, makes it one of the few proving grounds in the
nation where the three leading broadband technologies - cable,
telephone digital subscriber lines and fixed wireless - go head to
head for the residential and small-business market.
</P>
<P>
   The growing demand for broadband comes from a number of sources.
More families are buying computers and logging on to the Internet
from home than ever. A recent Rocky Mountain Poll indicated that
more than half of all Arizona homes have Internet access. And
people who have access to fast connections at work have grown
intolerant of waiting for Web pages to load at home.
</P>
<P>
   Demand is projected to accelerate as entertainment, telephone
service and home networking are enhanced by fast Internet
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Phone and cable companies such as US West and Cox enjoy a huge
head start in the race to bring broadband, generally defined as a
megabit or more per second, to the nation's houses. At a data rate
of a megabit, broadband can carry choppy video, but not
television-quality video.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprint, backing a technology formerly used for one-way
broadcast of subscription wireless television, may prove to be the
dark horse of the broadband race. &QL; 
FLAT VALLEY HELPS &QL; 
Sprint's technology, called fixed-wireless broadband, has some
advantages over its competition, which must extend or retrofit
existing systems of wires or cables that were not designed to
transmit data.
</P>
<P>
   The flat Valley is also well-suited to Sprint's transmission
towers, and the wireless network is easier and cheaper to build
than rivals' networks.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint says those strengths, combined with the radio spectrum it
has licensed in 90 U.S. cities, may allow it to make up ground
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   `We may be the largest broadband provider in the country in
three to five years,` said Robert Hoskins, Sprint Broadband
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   If a proposed merger with MCI WorldCom goes through, the
combined company will own licenses for the airwaves to over 66
percent of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   The analogy of a race is an apt description of the competition
among the three technologies because consumers don't have
preferences for one technology over the other. They just want fast
Internet access, said Kathie Hackler, broadband analyst for San
Jose, Calif.-based Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   The first company to their door at the right price is likely to
get and keep the business, she said. Each of the competing Internet
services is available for about $40 a month, though US West
requires an additional monthly fee for an Internet provider.
Consumers are further discouraged to switch technologies because of
the significant front-end costs of installation and hardware, which
can cost more than $200 each. Front-end costs are comparable for
all three technologies.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three broadband providers in the Phoenix area would
disclose subscriber totals. But it is clear that upgrades to phone
and cable systems have been expensive and slow, leaving many
neighborhoods without access. Sprint calls this unsatiated demand
`broadband envy` and says its wireless service offers a quick
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   With little promotion since its launch last month, Sprint says
its Valley subscriber base has doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint boasts that its hardware costs to bring service to a city
are measured in the hundreds of thousands of dollars, while
competitors' costs are measured in millions.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley, the company has two transmission towers, one on
South Mountain, the other on Shaw Butte in the north Valley. From
those two towers, it says, it can serve 85 percent of Valley homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's flat terrain is ideal for Sprint's wireless towers,
which require a clear line of sight from the tower to a home
antenna. The company is unlikely to get 85 percent coverage from
two towers in other cities, said Mike Paxton, broadband analyst for
Cahners In-Stat Group in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   WAY BEHIND &QL; 
The question, analysts say, is whether the advantages of wireless
are enough to overcome the huge leads that cable and digital
subscriber line phone technologies enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton said fixed wireless can't catch up, at least not in the
short haul.
</P>
<P>
   `They're way behind,` he said. `It will be 2002 before you see 1
million fixed wireless users. By then, there will be 10 million DSL
users and 7 million cable broadband subscribers.`
</P>
<P>
   However, Dataquest's Hackler hesitates to write off Sprint's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   `The (proposed) Sprint-MCI WorldCom merger makes this even more
interesting,` Hackler wrote in a May report on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   `A combined capability of 60 percent market coverage without the
limitations of wires makes this an even more interesting race.`
</P>
<P>
   Sprint faces other challenges for its national rollout.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the cable and phone companies, Sprint does not have
strong relationships with equipment providers, Paxton said.
Avoiding hardware shortages will be a hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   `The picture for cable and DSL is a lot clearer from the
manufacturing side,` Paxton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint will also have to overcome a shortage of skilled
technicians and avoid distractions from the pending merger, Hackler
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Jon.Sidener(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8169. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
