r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN     06-25 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS PUT END TO ANGELS' RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. -- For the first time in nearly two weeks, the
Anaheim Angels took the field Saturday night with a chance to make
up ground on first-place Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   They marked the occasion by allowing someone named Marcus Jensen
to drive in five runs - establishing a career high and doubling his
season total - and the lowly Minnesota Twins to romp to an 11-5
victory before 28,917 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who remain 5 games out of first place and 4 behind
second- place Seattle, failed for the fifth time this season to
extend a winning streak beyond three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels led 4-3 and had hit three consecutive homers off
Angels-killer Eric Milton, but after the third inning they went
meekly into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Milton, who no-hit the Angels last September and had a 21-inning
scoreless streak against them, didn't allow an Angel past first
base from the fourth until he completed his work after seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kent Bottenfield, returning after a stint on the
disabled list with tendinitis in his right shoulder, didn't look
sharp for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The young Twins, who started six players with less than two
years of big-league experience, were patient with Bottenfield and
were rewarded for their restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield walked four - two of whom scored - and the Twins'
big hits against him all went to the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen sliced a ground-rule double down the left-field line to
drive in two runs in the second. Former USC star Jacque Jones put
Minnesota ahead for good, 5-4, when he hit a homer down the
left-field line in the fourth, and Corey Koskie hit a 2-0 pitch
from Bottenfield to left center for a solo homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield left after five innings, having surrendered seven
hits, four walks and six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holtz pitched himself in and out of trouble in the fifth,
stranding runners at second and third but wasn't so fortunate in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   With David Ortiz at second and two out, Angels manager Mike
Scioscia ordered Denny Hocking intentionally walked so the
left-handed Holtz could face the switch-hitting Jensen, who was 0
for 18 batting right-handed this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen foiled the strategy by ripping a double to left-center
that scored Ortiz and Hocking and gave the Twins an 8-4 lead. He
drove in his fifth run with a ninth-inning groundout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-00 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
