r s BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN     06-25 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOTTER CRUISES TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Winning NASCAR Winston West races has not
been easy this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Dotter made it look a bit easier Saturday night. The
39-year-old from Charlotte, N.C., won the pole for the Home Depot
250 at Irwindale Speedway, took the lead for good with 50 laps to
go and won the race going away before a crowd of 6,490 people, the
largest crowd since opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Dotter is the first double winner in the series this year. He
won the last race, at Laguna Seca.
</P>
<P>
   Dotter, running in third place, went side by side with Steve
Portegna and leader John Borneman II on lap 200. Exiting turn 4 on
lap 202, Dotter, who raced in six NWWS races and was the crew chief
for Sammy Potashnick last year, got by both drivers for the lead.
When the yellow flag came out on lap 213 when Borneman hit the turn
3 wall with a flat right-front tire, the cars bunched up, but the
race was essentially over.
</P>
<P>
   On the restart, Dotter pulled away from second-place finisher
Brendan Gaughan - the series points leader - and won the race by
the length of a straight. Rookie Mike Duncan finished in third
place and Kevin Richards was fourth. Irwindale Super Late Model
points leader Greg Voigt - in his NWWS debut - finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   There were nine caution flags waved. They were primarily for
cars that hit the wall because of flat right-front tires. Only five
of the 26 cars failed to complete the race.
</P>
<P>
   Dotter earned $6,585 for the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000625.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      06-25 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BOLSTER DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ The first round of Satuday's National Hockey
League entry draft had a distinctly Swedish flavor for the Bruins,
who selected 18-year-old defenseman Lars Jonsson with the No. 7
overall pick and exercised their option to take the pick (acquired
from Colorado) at No. 27, grabbing 18-year-old left wing Martin
Samuelsson.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expected to play in Sweden next year and are
realistically a couple of years away from breaking into the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, who was born in Borlange, Sweden, had 38 points in 34
games for his Leksand junior team. He is a good skater with
excellent offensive skills. He was ranked 70th among Europeans in
the Central Scouting midterm report but moved to 11th at the end of
the year. The Bruins, who had been trying to make a deal to move up
in the draft up until 15 minutes before it began, had him rated
even higher and believed him to be the best available player at No.
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very offensive-minded on all levels that he has been
playing hockey,'' said Bruins scout Svenake Svensson, who has seen
a lot of both Jonsson and Samuelsson. ``Since he was about 13, he's
picked up a lot of awards every year in the youth program in
Sweden. He's very skillful offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, he needs to improve but he's not considered a
liability, only that his offensive skills are more developed than
those in his own end. Next year, Jonsson is expected to play in the
Swedish Elite League for Leksand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had 38 points in the junior league and that's amazing for a
defenseman,'' said Svensson of Jonsson's season last year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Central Scouting had him rated lower, Svensson
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys like blonde girls, some guys like red hair,'' he
said. ``It's a matter of taste maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson was ranked No. 9 among Europeans, up from No. 32 at
midseason, but a serious injury kept him sidelined for much of the
year and is the reason he was taken so late in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out 3 1/2 months in the middle of the season so it
affected it very much,'' said Samuelsson, who required surgery to
repair a broken bone in his right shoulder. Samuelsson played for
MoDo's junior team last year, scoring 17 points in 19 games, nine
of them goals. He said he has a contract with Hammerby in Stockholm
for next year, which is in a league a step below the Swedish Elite
League. He said he would be assured more playing time than if he
tried to play in the higher league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good move because it's pretty tough to (win) a
place on one of the Elite teams because the coaches have (a great
deal) of pressure on them,'' said Samuelsson.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't disappointed at going No. 27 because it's
still the first round even though he knew if he had been healthy,
it likely would've meant being picked earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ranked top five in the beginning of the season but after
the injury, I sunk very much,'' he said. ``I hoped that I would be
picked in the first round. That was what I dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said the team
elected to use Colorado's pick rather than wait until next year
because Samuelsson was available.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get him there we were extremely happy,'' said O'Connell.
``He played very well in the European Junior (tournament). He's a
highly skilled player, very fast and rugged. He could be the best
skater in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jonsson, O'Connell said they liked him because of his
offensive skills and hard shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs some work defensively but he's a smart kid and he's
very competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before they selected at No. 7, there was a lot of discussion at
the club's table. O'Connell said it was sparked by whether to take
Jonsson or another player, likely a forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was another player we really liked as well,'' he said.
``We figured both players could be impact players and we looked at
our depth in the organization and thought we needed (a defenseman)
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the draft, Boston had been hoping to make a deal to move
up in the No. 2-5 range but was unable to. There was also the
option of trading the pick to get immediate help, but O'Connell
said the Bruins decided to stay where they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know if there were any players available (to help
the team next year),'' he said. ``There might have been a couple
but the price was just too high. We felt it would have been a step
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
