<HEADLINE>
RED SOX TUMBLE INTO THIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ This is the difference between first and third place.
</P>
<P>
   When you're in first place, someone is apt to try and stick a
pie in your face, which was what Toronto closer Billy Koch was
attempting to do in a sneak attack on Blue Jays strongman Carlos
Delgado during a postgame TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   When you're in third place, your starting pitcher is sitting in
front of his cubicle, his voice choked with emotion while he tries
to fight back tears; your center fielder is cryptically suggesting
he knows what's wrong with the team but can't say; and your manager
stays behind closed doors for almost a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   That was the scene in the Red Sox clubhouse after the Sox
tumbled into third place for the first time since May 2 after a 6-4
loss to the Blue Jays in a newly popular SkyDome. A crowd of 30,130
showed up to see the home team make it two in a row over the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose, who is winless in his last six starts and fast
losing his grip on the slim thread holding him in the starting
rotation, was as vulnerable in the clubhouse as he was on the mound
Saturday afternoon. Rose, who gave up a two-run home run to Delgado
in the first and a two-run home run to Alex Gonzalez in the third,
was pulled with two outs in the third after Brad Fullmer reached on
an error by Nomar Garciaparra, the shortstop's third error this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was still shocked after the game that manager Jimy Williams
had come to get him, even though Gonzalez's home run had come right
after the Sox had tied the score at 2 on Garciaparra's home run in
the second and Carl Everett's RBI single in the top of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I don't have anything to say,'' said Rose. ``Anything
I say will get me in trouble. The situation is very hard. Yeah, I
was surprised (to be lifted). So many things are running through
your head. To go out there and try to compete is very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose has been working with pitching coach Joe Kerrigan on his
delivery. Asked what things were crowding his mind, he said:
``There are too many to talk about, but I can't pitch this way. Not
in this league. Not at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the possibility Rose will not pitch at this level for
much longer. Williams, when asked about Rose's place in the
rotation, said: ``We still have him scheduled to start in five
days, as we speak today.''
</P>
<P>
   That qualifier, of course, reserves Williams the right to change
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fed up,'' he said. ``I've got to do the things that make
me successful. If it takes going back three years to figure it out,
then maybe I've got to go back there,'' he said. ``I'm trying to
figure out what's going to make me better and help us as a team.
It's not fair to the bullpen to have to use them like that when I
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   In only three of his first 12 starts, Rose has finished six
innings. He has allowed 12 earned runs in his last 9 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox offense, meanwhile, continues to run on empty, even with
Jose Offerman back in the leadoff spot after a one-day absence
(sore left knee) and Garciaparra back at short after being limited
to DH duties Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon was out with a strained right hamstring, leaving
Everett flanked by two players (Curtis Pride and Darren Lewis), who
had one home run between them.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto starter Roy Halladay is a young righthander whose
circumstances mirror Rose's. He's a righthander who hadn't lived up
to expectations. Halladay had a 2-4 record and an 11.97 ERA when he
was sent to the Jays' minor league team in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was his first test, and after allowing Garciaparra's
home run, and three singles in the third, Halladay held the Sox
hitless until singles by Jeff Frye and Everett opened the eighth.
With reliever Paul Quantrill on the mound, Garciaparra's infield
out and Jason Varitek's RBI single made it 5-4, but Brad Fullmer
gave closer Koch and the Blue Jays a bigger comfort zone with a
home run in the bottom of the eighth off Rheal Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   Everett was asked if it was obvious the Sox are playing short.
``No,'' he said. ``We're playing well. Things don't happen for us.
I'm not going to state why we're not playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   That is no misprint. In the same paragraph, Everett said the
team was and wasn't playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are playing hard, but we're coming up short,'' Everett
said. ``There's a few reasons, but I can't mention them.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, mystery. Was the normally forthcoming Everett afraid he'd
get in trouble if he went public with his take on the team? ``I'm
not worried about myself getting in trouble,'' he said. ``It's just
not something you should know.''
</P>
<P>
   He did admit to one shortcoming he perceives. ``I know we're not
aggressive enough, for this team. We're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought there may be changes afoot, Everett said:
``Changes? Like what? Why? This team has been our squad. This is a
good team. We can't worry about what the front office might do.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the view is from third place _ the Sox are 1 1/2 games
behind the Blue Jays and a game behind the second-place Yankees _
it's not hard to detect some movement on the horizon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
