<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILBURY MOVES TO FORE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Acting like a man who closes his eyes at
night and sees his name on a pink slip, former Bruin Mike Milbury
took center stage at the NHL entry draft Saturday and attempted to
transform his Islanders from laughingstock to playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago considered the man who would lead the Bruins into
the 21st century, Milbury stole the show, pulling off three impact
trades and choosing Boston University netminder Rick DiPietro with
the first overall pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltending is the most important position in the sport,''
explained Milbury, who, just before selecting DiPietro, dealt away
netminders Kevin Weekes and Roberto Luongo in separate trades. ``We
are hanging a lot of our reputations on this kid (DiPietro).
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be crazy . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   But after missing the playoffs for a mind-numbing six straight
seasons, the Islanders, recently acquired by owners with deep,
cash-lined pockets, went into the two-day kiddie jamboree intent on
shopping their way back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the bold move to select DiPietro, the Winthrop, Mass.,
wunderkind, Milbury also masterminded these deals:
</P>
<P>
   --Shipped Weekes to the Lightning, along with towering defense
prospect Kristian Kudroc and a second-round pick, for a package of
draft picks that included Tampa's No. 5 overall. Four picks after
plucking DiPietro, the Isles then chose Raffi Torres, a
5-foot-11-inch fireplug left wing who can deal out stinging hits
and score.
</P>
<P>
   --Sent Luongo, once believed the game's brightest goaltending
prospect, and former Los Angeles Kings center Olli Jokinen to
Florida for a pair of young, impressive wings, Oleg Kvasha and Mark
Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   --Acquired elite defenseman Roman Hamrlik, the No. 1 pick in the
'92 draft by Tampa, from Edmonton for promising blue liner Eric
Brewer, forward Josh Green, and a second-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are not a better team immediately,'' Milbury said days
before the draft, ``and if we are not a playoff team in the very
near future, then it's off with my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the day's proceedings paled in comparison to the
actons of Move'em Milbury.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins raised some eyebrows by using both of their picks,
Nos. 7 and 27, to select Swedes, smooth-skating defenseman Lars
Jonsson and forward Martin Samuelsson, respectively. In opting for
Jonsson at No. 7, the Bruins discarded the conventional wisdom of
the league's Central Scouting Bureau, who rated Russians Mikhail
Yakubov and Pavel Vorobiev as the top two European positional
players in the draft. The Blackhawks, choosing 10th and 11th,
scooped up the two promising Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago general manager Mike Smith added some suspense to the
first round, calling a timeout before finally selecting Yakubov at
No. 10. Smith, who lives on Martha's Vineyard, could be seen making
phone calls at the Hawks' draft table, lending an air of a possible
blockbuster deal. He later explained that he attempted to trade the
No. 11 pick, but failed.
</P>
<P>
   The day's other significant deal, by Colorado, had a tangential
tie to the March 6 trade that sent Ray Bourque from the Bruins to
the Avalanche. Confident with their blue line after Bourque
recently signed to come back to Denver for at least one more year,
the Avalanche dealt offensive defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh to the
Carolina Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   A Group 2 free agent, Ozolinsh will command at least $4 million
a year with his next deal. It's a safe bet that the Avalanche
worked their way down the order of selection in the first round,
offering the enigmatic Ozolinsh to every NHL club for a
first-rounder, and finally got the Hurricanes to give up the prime
No. 14 pick. Carolina also sent defenseman Nolan Pratt to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sad,'' said a humble-looking Pierre Lacroix, the
Colorado GM, during a TV interview moments after the trade was
announced. No doubt, though, the Avalanche were glad to get out
from under Ozolinsh's deal, especially given the fact they owe
Bourque at least $6.5 million for his 2000-01 contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, now with Ozolinsh a key factor at the point on
their power play, also assuredly will allow veteran blue liner Paul
Coffey to leave as an unrestricted free agent. Look for the Maple
Leafs to move quickly and sign Coffey once he becomes a UFA July 1.
</P>
<P>
   From a New England standpoint, it was a mild surprise to see
UMass-Lowell defenseman Ron Hainsey selected before Boston College
blue liner Brooks Orpik. Hainsey was ranked ninth among North
Americans and went 13th overall to the Canadiens. Orpik, ranked
fourth overall in North America, drifted to Pittsburgh at No. 18.
Krys Kolanos, Orpik's teammate at BC, went with the next pick, to
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury made it clear that the Isles plan to plug DiPietro right
into the net this fall. With Weekes and Luongo gone, there are few
other options. The additions of Parrish, Kvasha, and Hamrlik bring
solid NHLers to Uniondale. If DiPietro is the real thing, then one
day of dizzying deals just may save Milbury that trip to the
guillotine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
