<HEADER>
A4222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-DIPIETRO-BOS &LR;      06-25 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DIPIETRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOALIE PROVES TOP SHELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Rick DiPietro and the New York Islanders made
history Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old former Boston University standout became the
first goaltender taken with the first overall pick in the National
Hockey League draft since it was modified in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   After general manager Mike Milbury traded former goalie of the
future Roberto Luongo as part of a multi-player swap to the Florida
Panthers, the stage was set for DiPietro to go in the top spot. In
a hectic day for Milbury, the Islanders also made a deal with Tampa
Bay for the No. 5 overall pick, with which they took forward Raffi
Torres. But the news of the day was DiPietro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really shifting assets here,'' said Milbury. ``We have a
different type of goalie in DiPietro. We were really wrenched over
the loss of Luongo, who's a quality kid and a quality goaltender.
He's a class act and a kid we would've been happy to ride with. But
as the draft progressed, it was clear that the value of Luongo was
greater than the value of the first overall pick. In our minds,
DiPietro possesses an element (stickhandling) that Roberto perhaps
doesn't possess. You could make an argument for either one.''
</P>
<P>
   For DiPietro, it was an exciting surprise even though it was
widely believed the Islanders had decided to take him No. 1 if a
deal for Luongo could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the teams were being kind of secretive about the
whole thing,'' said DiPietro. ``I really didn't know what was going
to happen. I was pleasantly surprised to hear my name called and
I'm just ecstatic right now.''
</P>
<P>
   By dishing goalie Kevin Weekes to Tampa Bay and Luongo to
Florida, DiPietro becomes both New York's goalie of the future and
the goalie of the urgent present.
</P>
<P>
   With the Islanders under new ownership that is committed to
spending, there is pressure to at least make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's going to be a lot of pressure put on me,''
said DiPietro. ``Roberto Luongo was an excellent goaltender. I
enjoy the pressure. I hope I'm ready for the next challenge, and
I'm going to do my best to make it possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step is signing him, which appears to be imminent. Paul
Krepelka of Woolf Associates, said he and Milbury talked into the
wee hours Friday night and that they are on the same page. Krepelka
seemed optimistic everything would work out.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1969, when the draft was altered from a format of
territorial picks to an overall amateur draft, teams have been
reluctant to take goaltenders early. Before DiPietro, Luongo was
the goalie taken highest when he was picked at No. 4 by the
Islanders in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Three goalies have been taken with the No. 5 pick _ Tom Barrasso
by Buffalo in 1983, John Davidson by St. Louis in 1973, and Ray
Martyniuk by Montreal in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Two were selected with the No. 6 pick _ Brian Finley (Nashville,
1999) and Michel Larocque (Montreal, 1972). Jamie Storr was picked
at No. 7 in 1994 by the Los Angeles Kings and twice goalies have
been taken at No. 8 _ Grant Fuhr by Edmonton in 1981 and Jimmy
Waite by Chicago in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro became just the fourth US-born prospect to be No. 1
overall. The others were Bryan Berard (Ottawa, 1995), Mike Modano
(Minnesota, 1988), and Brian Lawton (Minnesota, 1983).
</P>
<P>
   After choosing Luongo, the Islanders wanted to bring him along
slowly. From what Milbury said Saturday, there seems to be no such
plan for DiPietro, who is as well known for his confidence on the
ice as his deftness with a stick.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what changed his mind about DiPietro jumping into the
league at 18 vs. Luongo, Milbury said it was the player himself who
made him see things differently. ``His attitude,'' said Milbury,
``his approach to the game, his manner.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, from Winthrop, Mass., went from one year of college,
to opting into the draft, to being the No. 1 pick and likely
starting netminder for the Islanders when they open the season in
October. ``It's obviously very mind-boggling,'' said DiPietro.
``This was never something I thought would happen or even expected
to happen. And to have an opportunity to step in and be a big part
of the Islanders is something that I'm really looking forward to
and I'm really going to put a lot of effort into doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
