<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECE OF CAKE FOR INKSTER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ There was a birthday cake covered with
frosting, but for Juli Inkster the really sweet stuff had come in
the form of 18 holes of near-flawless golf that pushed her into
major view once again.
</P>
<P>
   Turning 40, said Inkster, felt great. Shooting a third-round
6-under-par 65 Saturday to get to 7-under 206 and a tie for the
lead at the McDonald's LPGA Championship was pretty good, too. ``I
did what I wanted to do,'' said the defending champion after
burning the back side at DuPont Country Club in 5-under 31, the
exclamation point being a birdie-birdie-birdie finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which probably is no surprise to the field at this second major
of the season. ``We all expect that of Juli,'' said Wendy Ward, who
dropped back into a tie with Inkster when she chopped up the
course's easiest hole, the 465-yard, par-5 16th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to cut (my drive) around the corner, but got it too
close to the tree limbs,'' said Ward, who had shaken off a bogey at
the par-4 seventh to run off five birdies in her next eight holes
to get to 8 under. The drive came to rest among trees, in thick
rough, ``300-plus yards away,'' and led to her first bogey on a par
5 in 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mishap, Ward can at least claim a share of the lead,
which is more than her playing partner, Laura Davies, can say. The
long-hitting, free-spirited Englishwoman was inexplicably sloppy
over a course she has come to love. A two-time winner of this major
at DuPont, Davies started the day with a two-shot lead over Ward
before crashing with a 75_211 that put her into a tie for seventh
at 2 under.
</P>
<P>
   Davies was the only name on the leaderboard to stumble, as
sub-par rounds ruled the day. Jan Stephenson, at 48 seeking her
first victory since 1987, posted her third straight red number, a
69_208, to move into third place, a shot ahead of Nancy Scranton
(67). Jane Crafter (69) and Michele Redman (70) are tied for fifth
at 3-under 210, while those at 2 under include Davies, the
ever-present Karrie Webb (69), 1998 champion Se Ri Pak (69), Wendy
Doolan (71), and the pride of Westford, Mass., Pat Bradley, who at
age 49 shot 67 and shared low round of the day until Inkster caught
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people who are 2 under or 1 under can get hot
and come from behind,'' said Inkster, who pointed the finger at
herself as Exhibit A. ``I got hot on the back side and came from
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotter than the weather, to be honest, because Inkster _ who
started the day tied for ninth at 1 under _ fell from the
leaderboard thanks to a three-putt bogey on the opening hole, then
casually ran off five pars to sit at even for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I got better as the day went on,'' said Inkster, who won
three majors before turning 30, then went nine years without
another before winning this title and her first US Women's Open in
1999. ``My swing is feeling a little better as the days are going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   She drained a 25-foot birdie putt on the par-4 seventh, then
followed with a 2-footer at the par-3 eighth. After making the turn
in 1-under 34, Inkster jumped from Page 2 to Page 1 of the
leaderboard with birdies at 10 and 11, then made four pars before
her grand finish _ a 2-foot tap-in at the 16th, a 12-footer at the
par-3 17th, and a 35-footer at the 18th in front of balloons and
dozens of well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was one person that didn't know it was my
birthday,'' said Inkster, whose lackluster 72-69 start had moved
the focus from her to players such as Davies, Stephenson, and Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Though Davies has a history of bouncing back in this tournament
(she wiped out a three-shot deficit and won here in 1996) and
Stephenson is a sentimental choice, the duty to play head-to-head
with Inkster falls to the unheralded Ward, 27, who is in her fifth
year on Tour and, despite two wins, is still trying to reach
personal goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I set as high expectations for myself as anybody possibly
could,'' said the 1994 US Women's Amateur champion and one-time
All-American at Arizona State. ``I think expectations are good.
They make you work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first real threat to win a major was put in motion _ make
that slow motion because she started with six pars, then made bogey
at the par-4 seventh _ with a string of four birdies, starting at
the 189-yard eighth hole when she drilled a 4-iron to within 18
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most consistent round I've played,'' said Ward,
who followed those four birdies with four straight pars, then her
fifth birdie of the day at the par-4 15th to get to 8 under.
</P>
<P>
   It ushered her to the 16th, which is where she gave back a shot,
but that small hiccup couldn't wipe the smile off her face. ``I
think I've got just as good a shot as anybody else to win,'' said
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster probably would say the same thing, viewing another LPGA
Championship as a perfect gift to go with the birthday cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
