<HEADLINE>
HALL OF FAMER CARNER HAS STOOD TEST OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ She concedes most of her competitors ``fly it
by me now,'' that back spasms flare up from time to time, and
playing four weeks in a row _ as she did earlier in the season _
drains her physically.
</P>
<P>
   Then you realize the woman telling you this is 61 years old and
has just birdied the closing hole to shoot 2-over 73 in a major
championship against players who are half her age. ``Up until this
year, I would kind of whip it up there with them,'' said JoAnne
Carner, who played in her 27th LPGA Championship this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Carner followed that 73 with a 76 and missed the cut for the
fourth straight year, but her presence is always a plus for golf;
she serves as a reminder that the game, though dominated these days
by a 24-year-old sensation, owes so many trailblazers who toiled
when the spotlight was not so bright.
</P>
<P>
   Carner's last trip to the winner's circle in an LPGA event took
place nearly 16 years ago, and it's been 24 years since that second
US Women's Open triumph established her as one of the game's
greats. From 1974 to 1983, Carner won her second US Open and put up
these Open finishes: three seconds, two thirds, a fourth, a sixth,
and a 10th. She has not won the LPGA Championship, but she has 12
top 10s, including a second when she was 53.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all that came after she virtually retired the US
Women's Amateur trophy, winning it five times. There are no regrets
about waiting until 1970, when she was 31, to turn pro because
money wasn't much of a factor in those days and, besides, she was
enjoying life.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshots of those wonderful days would most certainly include
the years she and her husband owned an executive golf course in
Seekonk, Mass. Don Carner was a salesman working in Providence and
he ``always wanted to own a golf course,'' said JoAnne. So he
crossed over the state line into Massachusetts and built a place
they called Firefly.
</P>
<P>
   The name suggests an explanation, and Carner laughs. It was
named by ``a drunken woman,'' who responded to Carner's plea. ``I
said, `I need a name for this place right now because it has to be
in the Yellow Pages in the morning,' '' said Carner. It was a hot
night and her friend slurred something about a firefly and thought
that was a fitting name.
</P>
<P>
   And so it became Firefly, home to some wonderful memories for
the Carners. In 1968, for instance, the day after ``The Great
Gundy'' _ short for Carner's maiden name Gunderson _ won her fifth
US Women's Amateur, she was back serving hot dogs at Firefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy turns and says to a customer, `JoAnne just won the Rhode
Island state championship,' '' said Carner, laughing pleasantly.
``Talk about coming down to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Carner turned pro and earned a whopping $14,551 in 1970, most of
it coming at something called the Wendell West Open, her first LPGA
Tour win. The first US Women's Open triumph came the next year and
on she went until 43 wins and admittance to the LPGA Hall of Fame
had been earned.
</P>
<P>
   The Carners sold Firefly in 1981, settling in Florida, where
fishing had become a favorite pastime. Most of her life was devoted
to caring for Don, who suffered from Parkinson's disease, and until
his death in January, they were inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Carner played in nine events last year, but might play 15 this
year. She'll see how she feels, but, yes, she gets a kick out of
trying to keep up with the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to, in my amateur days, have a nice, slow move through
the ball like she does,'' said Carner. ``When I turned pro, I got
more upright and started getting quicker, which was my downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is dominating the PGA Tour, and Carner wonders if
his competitors, seemingly running scared, could use the advice she
has been offering for years: ``Basically, when you play golf, you
don't watch anyone. I used to tell the rookies, look for four-leaf
clovers, anything to take your mind off of someone else's swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then her blue eyes come to life and Carner realizes that perhaps
even she wouldn't be able to stick to her words.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I played with Tiger, I'd have to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his final round at the US Open, Nick Faldo said his summer
schedule will be light _ the Loch Lomond, the British Open, the PGA
Championship _ because once points become available for next year's
European Ryder Cup team, he plans on playing as many as five events
in six weeks. If he's rediscovered some of his game, Faldo could
make things interesting because he wants Mark James replaced as an
assistant captain . . . Other US Open leftovers: Padraig Harrington
finished in a tie for fifth, but didn't agree with one reporter's
reference to him as a surprise. ``You're saying I'm a surprise, but
I'm plodding along on my own. If I finished fifth this week, that's
OK. I finished fifth before in a major, so it's nothing new. It may
be surprising people, but I'm not too worried.'' . . . Indeed, the
tournament was ``open'' to all candidates, but once it ended,
Jeffrey Wilson, the only amateur to make the cut, was back at work
selling Toyotas . . . Tom Kite plans on being at Southern Hills for
next year's Open (he's got two years left on his 10-year exemption
for winning in 1992), and both Watson and Hale Irwin said they'd
like to be there, even if it means going through sectional
qualifying . . . Vijay Singh, despite being the Masters champ,
didn't attract a lot of pre-tournament support at Pebble Beach and
the reason was simple: Observers were surprised by his decision to
change his putter and putting stroke so shortly after winning a
major. Though he closed with a 68 to finish in a tie for eighth,
Singh said he was ``very, very disappointed.'' . . . For the third
straight year, Paul Azinger finished top 15 to earn an exemption
next year . . . There's a simple recipe for beating Woods, said Lee
Janzen. ``Someone who can drive the ball 300 yards every time,
smart enough to play the right shots into the green, has the
imagination to curve the ball, strong enough to get out of any
rough, and holes every putt in sight.'' . . . Woods played the
tough 8-9-10 stretch in level par for four days. Colin Montgomerie
was 11 over for those holes . . . Bill Glasson recorded a double
eagle in the first round of the FedEx St. Jude Classic in Memphis,
using driver-driver on the 527-yard fifth hole. Not to be outdone,
Peter Mitchell did the same at this weekend's European Tour stop,
holing a 220-yard 4-iron. Then along came Sam Torrance with an ace
at the 174-yard par 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb said it would be an honor to meet Mickey Wright,
arguably the greatest player in women's golf history. ``I've been
fortunate enough to get to play with (most of the Hall of Famers),
but meeting Mickey Wright is one thing I have not done.'' . . .
Does Webb, like Woods, aspire to be the game's greatest? ``If I'm
just regarded by my peers as one of the best, that would be as much
as I could ever wish.'' Consider it done . . . Observers pointed
out that while Woods's 15-shot victory in the US Open was
phenomenal, Webb's victory in the Nabisco Championship _ 10 shots _
was not too shabby . . . The US Women's Open will certainly
dominate Webb's view come mid-July, but she isn't looking past a
July 10 charity event at Manhattan Woods CC in New York. It will
benefit the Christopher Reeve Foundation and the cause is dear to
Webb, for her longtime friend and coach in Australia, Kel Haller,
is a quadriplegic. ``Ten years ago, I remember sitting in a spinal
unit talking to my coach, who could not move from the neck down,''
said Webb. ``I spent four or five days in there with him and over
the period of time that he was in the hospital, I just said to
myself that even if Kel was still walking again, if I ever had the
chance to be able to contribute money, or help raise money to find
a cure for paralysis, then that's what I wanted to do.'' . . . Juli
Inkster said that come October, the US will be underdog in the
Solheim Cup in Scotland. That raised eyebrows, given the fact the
US has won four of the five events; but Annika Sorenstam, who most
certainly will anchor the European team, agreed. It will be called
the European team, but Sorenstam figures six Swedes have great
chances to make it . . . Who needs practice? Sorenstam's clubs
didn't arrive with her in France, so the first day she just walked
the course hitting a 7-iron borrowed from Helen Dobson. No problem.
Sorenstam eventually earned her third win of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
