<HEADLINE>
PAYOFF FOR LAKERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was almost six years ago to the day. The NBA was
getting ready to conduct its annual draft in 1994 and two
powerhouses were in the lottery, on their own, for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Picking ninth, following a 32-50 season in 1993-94, were the
Boston Celtics. Picking 10th, with a 33-49 season, were the Los
Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   On that June evening, the Lakers and the Celtics were, as was
the case throughout the previous decade, almost identical. This
time, however, they were among the have-nots, rather than the
haves. They had, for the first time in a while, been victimized by
a system they were accustomed to ruling.
</P>
<P>
   That previous year marked the first time in NBA history a player
from neither team participated in the All-Star game. The Celtics
had a playoff run of 14 years come to an end; the Lakers had gone
17 years since they failed to make the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had had two Hall of Famers retire (Larry Bird and
Kevin McHale) and were about to lose a third, Robert Parish, to
free agency. A fourth player, Reggie Lewis, had died. The Lakers
had lost Kareem Abdul-Jabbar to retirement and Magic Johnson had
contracted HIV. James Worthy had played his final game in an LA
uniform two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The draft unfolded in predictable fashion. Glenn Robinson, Jason
Kidd, and Grant Hill went 1-2-3. By the time the Celtics chose,
there was a division in the brain trust: consultant Bird favored
Temple guard Eddie Jones. But the man just recently installed as
the head of basketball operations by owner Paul Gaston saw Parish
leaving and Dee Brown already signed to a six-year deal. M.L. Carr
decided the team did not need another guard; it needed a center.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics chose Eric Montross. The Lakers chose Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   The teams have been separating ever since, with the Lakers
rising and the Celtics tumbling and treading water. Los Angeles's
recent title only serves to note how one team with history,
tradition, and grand expectations turned it around while another
team with history, tradition, and grand expectations is still stuck
in a rut.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics tried to rebuild through the draft, going so far as
to tank a whole season (1996-97) in hopes of getting Tim Duncan. It
didn't work. The Lakers rebuilt through trades and free agency and
basically ignored the draft with one major exception: 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers improved dramatically after their lottery foray,
going from 33 wins to 48 and advancing to the second round of the
playoffs. They benefited not only from Jones, but also from Cedric
Ceballos, who was acquired for a No. 1 pick, and from a new coach,
Del Harris. But it was the following year, 1996, that Lakers
general manager Jerry West had earmarked as the one that might
bring his franchise back to the top. Thinking, correctly, that a
new collective bargaining agreement might eliminate restricted free
agency, the Lakers cleared cap room to take a run at the most
potentially dominating man in the game: free agent-to-be Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, as they are doing now, threw good money at the
ordinary, re-signing Brown and Rick Fox. That year, they had no
real cap room, but they did have the sixth pick and took Antoine
Walker. The Lakers had the 24th pick and took Derek Fisher. But in
between, at 13, went Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were in the process of unloading players and
convinced Charlotte to draft Bryant at 13 and then deal him to LA
for center Vlade Divac. Who knows what would have happened had
Dallas (Samaki Walker), Indiana (Erick Dampier), Golden State (Todd
Fuller) or Cleveland (Vitaly Potapenko) taken Bryant. All we know
is that the four players taken ahead of him are no longer with the
team that drafted them.
</P>
<P>
   West spent a restless early July, jettisoning more salaries. He
somehow convinced Vancouver to take Anthony Peeler and George
Lynch, both of whom lasted a short spell in Canada. (Ex-Grizzlies
GM Stu Jackson deserves a Laker championship ring for bailing West
out.) He then had enough money, along with the other necessities,
to lure O'Neal to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The other LA first-round picks since Jones: Fisher, Sam
Jacobson, and Devean George. The Celtics' first-rounders since
Montross: Eric Williams, Walker, Ron Mercer, Chauncey Billups, and
Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it took four years and three coaches for the Lakers to
finally put it all together. But there was always the expectation
that it eventually would happen; it just depended on when Shaq got
``it'' and if he stayed healthy. He did both this season,
delivering a truly remarkable year.
</P>
<P>
   In short, one team gambled, was proactive, and went creative.
That team will be defending its championship next season. The other
team lost on purpose, raved about its draft picks, returned
regularly to the lottery, and then paid $50 million to a marquee
college coach. It still is right where it was six years ago,
picking in the lottery, hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA draft is Wednesday and no one has been busier than Magic
GM John Gabriel. Orlando has three of the first 13 picks, and that
means a lot of interviews, workouts, and nice dinners. ``It has
been incredibly exhausting,'' Gabriel said. ``Counting return
visits, we've probably had 45 guys come through.'' The Magic have
the fifth, 10th, and 13th picks, and Gabriel said the team likely
will hold on to two of them. What about all this talk about 5 and
10 to New Jersey for No. 1? ``I haven't talked to them since draft
day,'' Gabriel said. ``The thing with this draft is that it may be
easier to pick in the 7-10 range than it will be in the 2-5
range.'' The Bulls have two picks, 4 and 7, and the word is out
that they are not all that enthralled with Texas center Chris Mihm.
(In case you hadn't noticed, among the many Chicago needs is a big
man.) The Bulls had Minnesota shot-blocker Joel Przybilla in
Saturday for a second workout; he's a possibility at No. 7. Then
again, it could all be a Jerry Krause smoke screen; no one has seen
Mihm more this year than the accessible, affable Bulls general
manager. Jersey is still sitting at No. 1 and, with serious
questions about Jayson Williams and Kerry Kittles, may be looking
to get bodies and picks. Meanwhile, there's now talk that
high-schooler Darius Miles could go to the Clippers at No. 3, which
would be a mutual disaster . . . The status of Greek center Iakovos
Tsakalidis, meanwhile, continues to be murky. His Greek
representatives have hired veteran agent Bill Pollack, who insists
Tsakalidis will not return to AEK Athens next season under any
circumstances. ``That is not going to happen,'' Pollack said.
According to Pollack, AEK sent Tsakalidis a four-year, unilateral
contract on the kid's 21st birthday (June 10), a type of deal that
apparently is recognized only in Greece. But things have a way of
working out when drachmas are exchanged, although there has been no
buyout figure mentioned. Most NBA teams could pay only $350,000 _
the whole contract is reportedly around $1 million _ and, Pollack
said, ``The kid is willing to pay the difference. We just don't
have a number, and we may not have this resolved by draft day.''
Tsakalidis spent time recently in Florida recuperating from a bout
with bronchitis. He also had a recent workout with the Bulls . . .
Speaking of Chicago, center Will Perdue, who was released last
week, feels he has a shot at returning via the veteran's exception.
He turns 35 in August and would be eligible to make more than $1
million, a big drop from his $5.3 million salary last season. (Is
this a great country or what?) And Perdue's former Bulls teammate,
center Bill Wennington, who spent last season on the pine in
Sacramento (57 minutes over seven games), has decided enough is
enough and is calling it a career at the tender age of 37 . . . And
while we're on the subject, old friend Dino Radja, whose salary
finally comes off the Boston cap this year, has reached an
agreement to play for Olympiakos in Greece. It's being reported the
deal is for $2.2 million, but Eurosources say it's closer to $1.75
million. Rony Seikaly, whose endless arbitration case against the
Nets is close to being settled, is being courted by at least a
half-dozen teams in Europe. His preference is Greece, perhaps
Panathinaikos, but he also is holding out some hope of staying in
the NBA. He is 35.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's something to snack on. At least one general manager
thinks the Celtics are very interested in Keyon Dooling, the
6-foot-3-inch point guard from Missouri. He has been sort of a
``workout wonder,'' but the Celtics have Kenny Anderson under
contract for three more years at, basically, immovable numbers.
Yes, they could use help at the position. But at No. 11 in a draft
with no decent point guards? . . . So, is Shaq the next advertising
darling now that he has finally won one in the pros? Johnson thinks
not. ``Big men don't sell products,'' Magic said. ``So, can Shaq be
that man? No. That's just the way it is. He can be the best player
in the league, but he can't lead the league. There's a difference.
It's like it was with Kareem. Shaq's the most dominant. But we need
a guy to be The Man in terms of like Michael Jordan. So who is that
going to be?'' . . . And, a final note on Phil Jackson. An hour
before his team's critical Game 7 against Portland, the Lakers
coach was in his office in Staples Center. Was he going over film,
working the phone, doing the chalk thing? No. He was mending his
pants . . . Larry Bird is going to wait for a couple of months to
see what happens with his bid to buy the Celtics. That's why he
didn't stay in Indiana. There's also another reason: Bird wants to
be the man in control, and that would not be the case in Indy.
While he gets along with Donnie Walsh, there are two owners he'd
have to answer to, and that would not be the case if he was
fronting an ownership group in Boston. He would be the man. Bird,
as he told the Globe last February, has people lined up to make a
serious run at the team; one figure being mentioned recently is
$400 million. Bird apparently has one, very rich individual on the
West Coast who could do a Mark Cuban and simply write a check. And
what of Rick Pitino? Well, his buyout figure would be taken care of
by the seller, not the buyer. All of this is moot, of course, if
Gaston is determined to hold on to the team. But just in case you
may have forgotten, Gaston took over the controls prior to the
start of the 1993-94 season. That was the last time the Celtics and
the Lakers were equals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
