<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION GET BAD CREW CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The Revolution remain in first place in the
Eastern Division for the ninth straight week, but their lead is
slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   They generated little offense, and John Harkes made a fateful
deflection that led to the tiebreaking goal in a 3-1 loss to the
Columbus Crew Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have earned 26 points in 18 games, 1 more than
the MetroStars, who have played two fewer matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew converted the deciding goal in the 69th minute after
Harkes misplayed a ball near the center circle, sending it back
nearly 30 yards toward his own goal. Dante Washington outmaneuvered
Ivan McKinley, dodged a slide tackle from Brian Dunseth, and shot
off the right post. Jeff Cunningham scored on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes had performed well for most of the game, but this error
was costly. And the Revolution, instead of improving offensively as
the match continued, lacked the attacking threat to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard-paced ball and it hit hard off my left foot,''
Harkes said. ``It was just a reaction. Dante Washington then shoved
Ivan McKinley off the ball and took a shot. I was running back and
almost saved (Cunningham's) shot off the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes are what soccer is all about. We need to be better in
attack. Wolde (Harris) seemed like he was on his own. Teams are
able, over 90 minutes, to wear us down and find our weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Ramos converted a free kick to tie the score, 1-1, in
the 19th minute, and the Revolution were threatening through the
middle of the field and from long range. But in the second half,
Harris, the lone striker in a 4-5-1 alignment, had only one
threatening shot, a 30-yard blast that skimmed the top of the goal
as goalkeeper Matt Napoleon tumbled backward into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Fernando Clavijo blamed the deciding goal on inattention
by the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A player (McKinley) thought there should have been a foul
called and he stopped,'' Clavijo said. ``I tell the players every
day: `Do not stop until they see the flag go up and hear the
referee's whistle.' This was not a foul because I did not hear a
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's those little things that cost us games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were actually in possession before the goal. But
Leonel Alvarez's pass apparently surprised Harkes and ended up near
the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was played in by one of our midfielders,''
Washington said. ``I ran with (McKinley) and we both challenged for
it with a shoulder charge, which is legal, and he went down. I saw
Brian West but I didn't think I could get the ball to him, and
after one of their other players slid in, I shot off the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised the ball came out of midfield like
that, but once I saw it go back I went to pounce on it. It was a
very dangerous ball played into the box.''
</P>
<P>
   The play summarized the Revolution's night. It was the type of
pass Alvarez probably delivered to Colombian teammates thousands of
times in his career, a short, almost innocuous ball near the center
circle. But Harkes was not on the same wavelength, and it spoiled
what had been developing as a promising pairing in midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Alvarez and Harkes will have another chance to compensate
since they will likely be the centers of attention when the
Revolution visit Miami July 4. Ramos will be suspended for
excessive cautions after receiving a yellow card in the 42d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Sommer brought an imposing presence to the goalkeeper
position in his MLS season debut, but was betrayed by an Adam Eyre
misplay in the 15th minute that led to a Jason Farrell goal. On the
third goal, by John Wilmar Perez, the Revolution, already missing
Rusty Pierce (back) and Mauricio Wright (suspended), had switched
to a gambling, three-man defense against three speedy Columbus
attackers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
