<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS SET TO REKINDLE LOVE AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pete Sampras in love probably isn't as big a story in
this town as ``Shakespeare in Love.'' I mean, it's not a major
movie, but that doesn't mean it won't be. The Bard was here first,
and that gives him an edge, but Pete has his midsummer night's
dream, too: a seventh Wimbledon championship.
</P>
<P>
   Seven smash hits on Centre Court _ a tennis yard that is built a
lot like Shakespeare's Globe Theatre _ would make him a leading man
strutting the stage of two centuries as the Bard did in overlapping
the 16th and 17th. His quest for the first of the 21st begins
Monday. Opening the two-week show for the sixth time _ the
champion's traditional privilege _ Pete will audition a bit player
named Jiri Vanek from the Czech Republic for the role of a fall
guy.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to look past Vanek, No. 81 in the world, and back a
long way to find the man just plain Pete is seriously chasing: an
Edwardian dandy, William Charles Renshaw, who preferred to be
called Willie. He was seldom called on to offer a losing handshake
while setting the house record of seven titles between 1881 and
1889, the first six consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Willie lost one final, 1890; Pete has lost none. The drill is a
little tougher in our era of Pete I. The lucky number in this
crapshoot also is seven. Seven wins and you clean the table.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Renshaw's task was simplified by the challenge-round
system of his day. The defending champion hung out idly until the
last day of the tournament, when he was expected to break a sweat
by playing one match against the survivor of the tournament proper:
the challenger. That format lasted until 1922, when everybody
started as equal as today. Thus, Willie's six straight titles
covered only 10 matches. He was 22-3 lifetime here, while Sampras
is 52-5.
</P>
<P>
   But, back to Pete in love. His Juliet is an American television
actress named Bridgette Wilson, for whom the perfect engagement
ring would glitter with 20 diamonds: a Renshaw-tying seventh
Wimbledon plus an Emerson-eclipsing 13th major title. Oh, yes,
Aussie Roy Emerson, who won his 12th major _ the French _ 33 years
ago, is the other pigeon on Pete's hunting list.
</P>
<P>
   Pete actually fell for the Sporting Lady of London SW 19 _
Centre Court _ long before setting eyes on Bridgette, his recently
declared fiancee. Often referred to as feminine (like a ship) by
her beauticians, CeeCee is a capricious shrew Pete has tamed better
than anyone before him. (Renshaw's titles were won on her
predecessor at the Worple Road Ground, abandoned in 1922.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about Centre Court a lot as a kid playing on
concrete in Southern California,'' Sampras said. ``I always felt
when I changed my game to serve-and-volley'' _ from double-fisted
backhanding and baselining _ ``that grass was going to be the
surface I was going to break through on, and I would love playing
on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, love at first smite. The memory is of Pete
as an unhappy, puzzled, and lonely-looking teenager in 1989, when
he made his debut in a defeat, to Todd Woodbridge on Court 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, actually it was much different,'' Sampras said. ``I was
18 when I came over to Wimbledon, and I didn't like the surface.
Couldn't really return that well. Didn't like the bad bounces.
Really had a pessimistic attitude on grass. It wasn't until I
started working with (coach) Tim Gullikson, and then in 1992 got to
the semis of Wimbledon. It wasn't until that point that I felt like
I could possibly win here. I didn't realize I was going to win the
next six out of seven, but I think that in 1992 I was able to kind
of get over the hump and realize that I was able to play well on
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson, who died in 1996, oversaw the installation of an
invaluable chip backhand. At first, Pete thought it was
old-fashioned stuff, a la his targets, Renshaw and Emerson. But any
hacker at Boston's Longwood Cricket Club could have told the
reluctant kid that it's a necessity for winning on the green. Even
backcourt-haunting Bjorn Borg developed effective
chipping-and-charging, awkward-looking though it was with his
two-hander, as he won five straight Wimbledons, and became enamored
of CeeCee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My appreciation of Centre has gotten greater and greater over
the years,'' Sampras said. ``I just love it. The other day I just
went down to the club, had a workout, and walked around the
grounds. I made a special trip to Centre and just, you just stand
there and look around at the stadium, look at the court, look how
plush it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk through the gates, you look at the place, the grass,
and how green it is. No sponsors signs like you see in other
stadiums, and it is definitely _ it is our biggest tournament. It's
our Super Bowl. You walk on Centre, it's like a cathedral. You
don't feel that really anywhere except for Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved watching the tournament on TV as a kid, and now I've
won here six times, and certainly I'd like to add to that over the
next four, five years. I feel like the whole world is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be watching again as he romances Centre once more. He
wasn't admitted to her sanctum, beguiled by her charms, until 1992,
a victory over the same Aussie, Woodbridge, who had spoiled Pete's
coming-out party three years before. He has lost only twice on the
planet's prime tennis plot: to Goran Ivanisevic in the 1992 semis,
and to Richard Krajicek in the 1996 quarters. Krajicek, who
succeeded Pete as champ, is the lone scratch on the chrome of 46
victories in his last 47 Wimbledon starts.
</P>
<P>
   With his loves, Bridgette and CeeCee, nearby, Pete will have it,
in the Bard's words, ``As you like it!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
