<HEADLINE>
TWINS PUT END TO ANGELS' RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kent Bottenfield, wearing a print shirt and
shorts, was the picture of comfort as he stood at his locker.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was the Minnesota Twins looked the same way at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins, behind five RBI from Marcus Jensen, welcomed
Bottenfield back from the disabled list by digging in and peppering
the right-hander in an 11-5 victory over the Anaheim Angels before
28,917 Saturday night at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The loss prevented the Angels from making up any ground on
Oakland, which had its nine-game winning streak snapped, and left
them 5 games out of first place and 4 games behind second-place
Seattle in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   It also marked the fifth time this season that the Angels have
failed to extend a winning streak past three games.
</P>
<P>
   The sore shoulder that sent Bottenfield to the disabled list was
fine. Not so for his countenance.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, he said, there will be no more Mr. Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   After the Twins delivered three big hits --- a ground-rule
double by Jensen and homers by Jacque Jones and Corey Koskie --- to
the opposite field, Bottenfield came to the conclusion that he must
pitch inside more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, but I pitched like crap,'' Bottenfield said.
``They had a lot of guys diving and that's got to stop. I didn't
back guys off the plate. They were too comfortable at the plate.
I've given up 16 homers and that's got to stop. Guys have been too
comfortable for the last 2 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys feet are set, they call time out and dig in a little
more. Bob Gibson and Don Drysdale would knock them down the first
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, who struck out nine against Tampa Bay last month by
working inside, nibbled at the strike zone as if he were eating a
sandwich crust first.
</P>
<P>
   He walked four batters --- two of whom scored --- and even when
he was ahead of the Twins, he had a hard time putting them away in
his five innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield struck out four, but three were in the first two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jones' home run that irked Bottenfield most.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who lunged at a low and away offspeed pitch, hit a fly
ball that landed just inside the foul pole down the left-field line
and put Minnesota ahead for good, 5-4, in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the second-year center fielder from USC, said it was
clear after the first time through the order that Bottenfield was
willing to live on the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually he didn't come in unless he was deep in the count,''
Jones said. ``He was throwing a lot of pitches away and we
recognized that. If he's going to beat you, then you want to make
him beat you in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins handed a 3-0 lead to Angel-killer Eric Milton, but
consecutive homers by Garret Anderson, Troy Glaus and Scott Spiezio
--- all on letter-high fastballs --- evened the score in the
second. It was the second time this season that the Angels have hit
three consecutive homers.
</P>
<P>
   Benji Gil, who tied a career high with three hits, scored on
Anderson's single in the third to give the Angels a 4-3 lead, but
it proved to be a paradise lost against Milton. The left-hander,
who no-hit the Angels in September and entered the game with a
20-inning scoreless streak against them, didn't allow a runner into
scoring position until he left at the end of the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   By then the Twins owned an 8-4 lead and they added three more
against Shigetoshi Hasegawa in the ninth. Injury was added to
insult when Glaus, whose homer was his team-leading 23rd of the
season, left with back spasms in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who was in the DH role because of the spasms, is expected
to take today off.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear in the seventh that it just wasn't the Angels'
night.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia walked Denny Hocking with two out
and a runner at second only to have Jensen, 0 for 18 as a
right-handed batter this season, drive a two-run double to
left-center. Jensen, who entered the game with a .176 average, had
a ninth-inning RBI to double his season total in one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just flat out beat us,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
