<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORPIK SLIPS A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-ORPIK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Brooks Orpik had to a wait a little longer
than he expected Saturday to be selected in the NHL entry draft.
The Boston College blue liner, ranked as the second-best defenseman
available in North America, wasn't picked until 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the surprise, he went to the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were probably the only team that didn't interview me,''
said Orpik, who had no fewer than three interviews with the
Edmonton Oilers, who owned the 17th pick. ``I'd be lying if I said
I wasn't getting a little anxious. From everything I heard, I
thought I'd go in the top 10. But it's not a day to be
disappointed. I couldn't be any happier than the way things worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The other interesting twist, from a New England perspective, was
that University of Lowell blue liner Ron Hainsey, from Bolton,
Conn., was claimed ahead of Orpik, selected 13th overall by the
Canadiens. The NHL's Central Scouting Bureau figured the
smooth-skating Hainsey to be the third-best North American blue
liner available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised, again because of the rankings,''
said Orpik, reflecting on Hainsey going ahead of him. ``Some of it
is based on what a team needs, so that factors in, too. I'm glad to
see it for him. He's a good player _ we played together in the
World Junior tournament in Sweden.''
</P>
<P>
   Orpik, from East Amherst, N.Y., planned to celebrate a little
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in Calgary, beginning with a barbecue at the home
of Krys Kolanos, his BC teammate who was selected 19th overall by
the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Orpik, Kolanos, who projects as a scoring wing in the
NHL, had a feeling the Coyotes would take him. He met with
management before the draft and picked up vibes that he might be a
Desert Dog before the day was out. Nonetheless, when he heard his
named called in Calgary, his hometown, he wasn't prepared for his
emotional reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing's exhilarating,'' he said. ``I had butterflies
all morning. When the time came, I was shaking. I think my legs
went numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Patrick, the Pittsburgh general manager, and his Phoenix
counterpart, Bobby Smith, both said they figure they'll wait awhile
before signing the BC players. Unless things change dramatically
over the summer _ and money often changes everything _ Jerry York
likely will have both of them back in the Eagles' lineup for the
2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really encourage that here,'' said York, whose squad made it
to the Frozen Four again this spring. ``I like the fact they get
their education and their athletics. In a perfect world, they'll
have long NHL careers, and with their degrees, they'll have
something to fall back on when they're done with hockey at the
ancient age of, say, 37 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   York compared Orpik with Dallas defenseman Derian Hatcher, one
of the NHL's best hitters. Hainsey, he said, was more like
Detroit's Nicklas Lidstrom, more of a puckhandling defenseman who
can man the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hainsey's a very good player,'' he said. ``He's got great
offensive skills. My guy's bigger and stonger, more physical.
Hainsey's probably quicker. When you're making those kind of
choices, it's an eye-of-the-beholder thing. It's not so much who
the player is as what kind of player he is.''
</P>
<P>
   One key factor in Orpik getting scooped by the Penguins was
Pittsburgh scout Neil Shea, an ex-Eagle who has kept a watchful eye
over the blossoming prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him inside and out,'' said an ecstatic Shea, explaining
how the Penguins selected Orpik without having first interviewed
him. ``When he was still there, there was absolutely no debate _ he
was our guy. Done. He's got great character, great work ethic. I'd
be shocked if there is anyone in this draft with better work
ethic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
