<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACTAVISH HAS WHAT IT TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ The Oilers made a good choice Thursday by
naming Craig MacTavish their head coach. Mac-T, as he came to be
known here in his playing days with the Bruins in the early '80s,
is bright and energetic, well spoken, and honest.
</P>
<P>
   Now 41 years old, MacTavish made the point in his news
conference of saying he inherited a quality team. OK, we'll let him
stretch the truth a little, first day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers have some good, young talent, but they're merely a
shell of the great Edmonton squads that won five Cups, three with
MacTavish in uniform, during the Northern Alberta dynasty years.
For the better part of 10 years now, the Oilers have been fighting
the bloody battle of a Canadian small-market team in a league with
spiraling player salaries and an ever-shrinking Canadian dollar
(vs. America's coin of the realm).
</P>
<P>
   The drudgery finally got to Glen Sather, leading the architect
of those great Oilers squads to bolt to New York this spring as the
Rangers' makeover man. His departure was his white flag of
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one is better qualified than MacTavish to deal with
restrictions. He learned how to cope with a minimum when he served
his one-year sentence in the Massachusetts penal system, after
pleading guilty to vehicular homicide in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling north on Route 1 in Peabody, after a few hours of
merriment, MacTavish rear-ended a Ford Pinto driven by Kim Radley,
a 26-year-old antiques dealer from West Newfield, Maine. Radley's
car flipped, trapping her inside, and four days later she died of
head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   MacTavish spent three months of his sentence in a 40-square-foot
cell, about twice the size of a net opening, at the Essex County
House of Correction, the Salem jail built in 1812. During lockdown
hours, from 8 p.m. to 9 a.m., there were no bathroom privileges,
beyond the standard-issue bucket tucked into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   MacTavish has spoken little of his days in the lockup. Upon his
release, he told the Globe's Michael Madden, ``When people hear my
name now, I'm sure they're going to say, `There's Craig MacTavish _
he made that terrible mistake.' ''
</P>
<P>
   More than 15 years later, MacTavish has four Stanley Cup rings
(three with the Oilers, one with the Rangers), and  &UR; today &LR;  he has
the charge of trying to help rebuild a franchise that can barely
survive in today's NHL economic environment.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, MacTavish has been a solid citizen on and off
the ice from the time he was set free. If there were whispers
(``There's Craig MacTavish . . . ''), they have faded with time.
Given a second chance, he thrived. Now we find out if he can teach
others to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember, free agency begins Saturday. A little more than two
months ago, when he was retained as Bruins coach, Pat Burns said he
couldn't stop smiling over the prospect of some of the names Harry
Sinden and Mike O'Connell tossed around as possible free agent
hires in the Hub. Now we get to see if there is any bite behind the
smile. If Don Sweeney packs up as expected _ look for Mike Milbury
to make a serious bid to lure him to Long Island _ it will be all
the more imperative for Sinden and O'Connell to add experience to
the back line. Lyle Odelein, last seen in Phoenix (claimed Friday
by Columbus), might fit the job description and the payroll (about
$2 million a year). He also has the nasty streak the Bruins
desperately need. For skill, hard-shooting Vladimir Malakhov could
be the best blue liner available, but he made $4 million last year,
making him an uneasy financial fit here . . . Rumors circulated in
Philadelphia early last week that ex-Bruin Ray Bourque was on his
way from Denver to Philly in a swap for Eric Lindros and/or Chris
Therien. ``Preposterous, that's the only word I can attach to
that,'' said Steve Freyer, who only days before negotiated the deal
that brought Bourque back to the Avalanche for at least one more
season. ``There were very specific reasons the Avs wanted to sign
Ray _ specifics I can't repeat. But they made it clear to us that
they see Ray as an integral part of the team, a key part of what
they need to get to the next level.'' . . . New Jersey netminder
Martin Brodeur, now with his name on the Stanley Cup twice,
sometimes doesn't get enough credit for his puckhandling skills.
``His greatest skill may be his ability to see the play
unfolding,'' says former netminder John Davidson. ``He is so fast
at that. It's like a quarterback who has the ability to read the
rush. He can take that instant picture with his mind. When I
played, I'd take the picture, too, but I'd have to take the film to
a pharmacy, drop it off, and pick up the pictures two days later.
It's too late then. Brodeur's got an Instamatic.'' . . . Guy
Carbonneau hasn't said for sure, but the bet around Dallas is that
the NHL's oldest performer (40) will be back for another season
with the Stars. ``If he left, the place we would miss him most is
on the ice,'' said Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock, noting that Carbo's
value is more than just a voice of experience in the dressing room.
``He's out there for the last minute of every period. Where do you
find those kinds of guys?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs figured they would lose Kevyn Adams, once a Bruins'
first-round draft pick, in Friday's expansion draft. They were
right. Adams joined ex-Bruins Mattias Timander and Steve Heinze on
the Columbus Blue Jackets' roster. Toronto could have kept Adams on
its protected list, but it would have come at the risk of leaving
another ex-Bruin, Dmitri Khristich, exposed. But what would have
been the risk, really? Khristich's deal next season calls for $3
million, and neither the Blue Jackets nor the Wild would have
interest in spending that kind of coin for someone with Khristich's
inconsistency . . . Another story out of Philly last week had Roger
Neilson, bumped off the Flyers' head coaching job by Craig Ramsay,
weighing an offer from Tampa Bay to be the Bolts' associate head
coach and assistant GM. Only one problem, said Lightning GM Rick
Dudley, there was no offer to Neilson . . . No doubt Dudley ruffled
some feathers just hours before the draft when he accused GMs of
years past of being a sleepy lot. Dudley: ``Being conservative has
been a way of life for NHL executives for 1,000 years. It's not
that way anymore.'' That sense of leave-it-alone lethargy, however,
rendered a good many franchises stagnant in the '80s and '90s.
Dudley arrived in Tampa Bay with picks 5 and 8 in the first round
and made it clear he was eager to deal for a player or two who
could make an impact in 2000-01 . . . If they stick to their stated
mission, the Flames will go up for sale this week, undoubtedly
destined for a US city, unless they sell 1,300-plus season tickets
in the next five days. But don't be surprised if ownership,
encouraged by a 25 percent increase in season tickets since
season's end, keeps the Flames in place for at least one more
season . . . Freyer will be looking to find former BU blue liner
Jon Coleman a job after July 1. San Jose property, he just wrapped
up his third year in the minors, with a marked improvement in his
plus-minus, from minus-20 in 1998-99 to plus-17 in 1999-00.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrator Lawrence Holden has to render his Alexei Yashin
decision this week, determining whether Ottawa's estranged center
is a Group 2 free agent or whether he must come back to the
Senators and work for the $3.6 million on the last year of his
deal. Either way, look for Yashin to be dealt. The hottest rumor
recently had him going to Chicago for a package that included
Alexei Zhamnov, Anders Eriksson, junior center Mark Bell (the No. 8
pick in '98), and a first-round draft choice. GM Mike Smith
promptly struck that one down before the draft, saying, ``There's a
limited market for disgruntled players asking for $8 million, $10
million, or $11 million a year.'' . . . Don't bet against the
Islanders getting into the Yashin hunt. They need a legitimate
franchise player and Milbury, with new ownership approved by league
governors last week, has permission to spend and a mandate to shape
a competitive team . . . Phil Esposito, who won't be returning to
Ch. 38 as a color man this season, says he'd like to join an NHL
front office, assessing talent and aiding in player-personnel moves
. . . For those who may have forgotten the worst trade in Bruins
history: After selecting Ken Dryden 14th overall in the 1964 draft
(four rounds, 24 players), the Bruins swapped the future Hall of
Famer to the Canadiens, along with Alec Campbell, for Guy Allen and
Paul Reid. None of the other three players in the trade ever played
in the NHL. ``I won't say who it was,'' recalled Ron Caron, who in
later years ran the draft for Montreal, ``but I am sure someone
made a call to (former Canadiens GM) Sam Pollock and said, `You
know, Sam, you made a mistake. You should have taken Dryden.'' . .
. If the Flyers don't offer Lindros at least a one-year deal at
$8.5 million by Friday night, he becomes an unrestricted free
agent. One possible reason for the delay: industry-wide, for all
sports, it is becoming considerably more costly to insure athletes
against injury. Some underwriters have left the business entirely.
Others have jacked up the premiums to absurd levels. If the Flyers
want to take the risk of signing L'Enfant Terrible, even with his
history of concussions, they might not be able to mitigate that
risk, even by spending another $1 million or $2 million as a hedge
against catastrophic injury . . . The Sharks don't figure to bring
back Jeff Norton, of Acton and Cushing Academy, at his $2.5 million
option. At the right price ($1 million?), he could still lend some
stability to a blue line . . . The three veterans Colorado exposed
in the expansion draft were all ex-Bruins: Dave Andreychuk, Jeff
Odgers, and Dave Reid. Of the three, only Reid is certain to return
to the Avalanche next season. Odgers and ex-Bruins Joe Juneau
(Ottawa) and Cam Stewart (Florida) got picked by the Wild.
Minnesota traded Juneau to Phoenix for Swedish prospect Rickard
Wallin, a center . . . Overlooked in all the hype surrounding BU
goalie Rick DiPietro in this weekend's draft: The Wild recently
signed St. Lawrence free agent Derek Gustafson, the freshman who
backstopped Joe Marsh's Saints to the Frozen Four. Gustafson, who
turned 21 last week, was the ECAC rookie of the year with marks of
17-4-2, a 2.09 goals-against average, and a .936 save percentage.
He stopped 72 BU shots in the Saints' victory in the NCAA regional
that went to four OTs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers left Alexandre Daigle exposed for Castaway Friday,
the expansion draft that stocked Columbus and Minnesota. To no
one's surprise, he remained Blueshirt property _ at least until
Sather drops him or moves him for a bucket of pucks. Late in the
1999-00 season, then-coach John Muckler went around the Rangers
dressing room, asking each player what it would mean to them if the
club made the playoffs. According to Muckler, Daigle said, ``It
means, if I play well, I'll get another contract.'' Muckler's
response: ``Wrong answer.'' Muckler doesn't believe hockey is the
first priority in Daigle's life. ``He likes everything about hockey
_ except the playing,'' said Muckler . . . One voice in the know
believes the Penguins at least will extend Kevin Stevens an
invitation to training camp in September. Former Rangers GM Neil
Smith had a deal worked out to send Stevens to the Penguins late in
the season, but the swap was derailed when Stevens was arrested in
March for possession of crack cocaine . . . Remember the days when
it seemed the Canadiens entered the draft with at least a pair of
first-round picks? Witness, in '68 they held the top three picks:
1. Michel Plasse, 2. Roger Belisle, and 3. Jim Pritchard, and
followed a year later with picks No. 1 (Rejean Houle) and 2 (Marc
Tardif). Well, Saturday they entered with two first-round picks (13
and 16) for the first time since 1985, when they took Jose
Charbonneau (12) and Tom Chorske (16) . . . Deron Quint, of Tabor
Academy and the 30th pick overall (Winnipeg) in the 1994 draft,
went into Saturday hoping the Devils finally would deal him. Quint
was exiled within days after the Devils acquired him from Phoenix,
GM Lou Lamoriello firmly stating he would never again pull on a
Devils sweater . . . Evgeny Ryabchikov, wherever you are, here's
hoping you invested that signing bonus wisely.
</P>
</TEXT>
