<HEADLINE>
TURNABOUT DOESN'T PLEASE INTIMIDATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It may be a well-worn cliche, but what goes around
usually comes around, especially in racing. Jeremy Mayfield's
``bump and run'' victory over Dale Earnhardt in last Monday's
Pocono 500 was proof positive.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's triumph, in which he bumped Earnhardt's black No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet from behind on the final lap to cause the
Intimidator to fall out of the lead, was akin to the class runt
whuppin' up on the schoolyard bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intentionally tried to wreck him or anything,''
Mayfield said, afterward. ``We just wanted to rattle his cage a
little bit, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's comments were an obvious aside to identical remarks
Earnhardt made last August at Bristol, Tenn., where he rear-ended
Terry Labonte on the last lap to win the race, saying afterward he
only meant to rattle Labonte's cage.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayfield took his victory lap around the 2.5-mile triangular
track at Pocono International Raceway, receiving the thumbs up from
many of his colleagues, Earnhardt pulled alongside Mayfield's No.
12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus and offered his own one-fingered salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him he was No. 1,'' Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   This is why people love NASCAR so much _ because the drivers'
raw and unfiltered emotions often spill out onto the track, adding
a good-vs.-evil element of conflict to the plot of each week's
event. If Sunday's Save Mart/Kragen 300 at Sears Point Raceway were
billed as a World Wrestling Federation steel cage match, the
headline bout no doubt would pit the Intimidator vs. the Defiant
One.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like he hit me,'' Earnhardt said of Mayfield's rough
tactics. ``I don't know if he did or not. He took the air off
something. It hadn't done that before with any cars behind me. He
got me. He drove that sucker 10 car-lengths deeper than he had been
driving it all day.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mayfield countered with the same defense Earnhardt has often
used himself in such circumstances (and there have been many
throughout his 21-year career).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard-nosed racing,'' said Mayfield, who joined Tony
Stewart and Dale Earnhardt Jr. as the only two-time winners this
season. ``A lot of people talk about Dale Earnhardt coming up the
hard way and driving that way. So did I. I just haven't been in the
situation to do that yet. I'm just as hard-nosed as he is. You have
to do what you have to do to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't forgotten about the 10 times he got me,'' he added.
``I'm not intimidated by Dale Earnhardt, and never will be.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mayfield won the undying admiration of his peers
(``Earnhardt got a little bit of his own medicine, and everybody
knows it,'' said one driver), he seemed to become a NASCAR cult
hero.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to his Lake Norman, N.C., home Monday night,
his answering machine malfunctioned after it was flooded with
congratulatory messages. A backup also went on the blink. Then, on
Tuesday, Mayfield participated in an online chat on NASCAR's Web
site and was besieged with a record 61,000 hits, nearly 10 times
the normal amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound weird, but it was like a dream-come-true race
for me,'' Mayfield said. ``To win like this, to pass Dale
Earnhardt, to come to the final corner and get him loose and then
do that, I don't think I can ever top that one in terms of wins.
That's pretty awesome. If I don't do anything else in my career
that will mean a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a total loss of a weekend for Earnhardt. Although he
was thwarted from a victory that may have vaulted him into the
points lead _ he remains 57 points behind leader Bobby Labonte
headed into Sunday's race at Sonoma, Calif. _ Earnhardt did receive
a warm Father's Day gift from his oldest son Kerry, who recorded
the first victory of his career in last Saturday's ARCA race at
Pocono . . . Jeff Gordon, who has won the last five straight road
races on the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit, will attempt to extend his
streak to six Sunday at Sears Point, Calif., where last year he
battled flu-like symptoms and searing heat that sapped him of his
energy and left him barely able to climb out of his car in Victory
Lane. This year, Gordon knows he'll face some stiff competition
from savvy road course racers such as Mark Martin, Rusty Wallace,
Ricky Rudd, Scott Pruett, Jerry Nadeau, Robby Gordon, and Wally
Dallenbach. ``There are so many guys who can win,'' said Gordon,
who has won only once in 15 races this season. ``Of course, you've
got Mark Martin, who chased me last year, and Rusty Wallace. I used
to watch Scott Pruett race go-karts here (at Sonoma) and he's
tough, and a road racer like Jerry Nadeau will be very strong. I
could go on, but you will have a lot of guys who will improve on
what they had.'' . . . Tracy Gordon (no relation to Jeff) is on a
bit of a roll in the Busch North Series. Gordon, of Strong, Maine,
captured his third consecutive victory last weekend at Jennerstown,
Pa., to go along with triumphs at Holland (N.Y.) International
Speedway June 3 and at Beech Ridge Motor Speedway in Scarborough,
Maine, June 10. ``We have been very fortunate the past three
weeks,'' said Gordon, who leads Brad Leighton by 52 points in the
driver standings. ``We have hit on a combination that is working
right now and we hope that it leads to the series championship.
That is our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Rahal, who was installed as CART's interim president and
CEO after Andrew Craig was forced to resign last week, attended a
state dinner at the White House last Tuesday night honoring the
King of Morocco. During a teleconference Wednesday, Rahal joked
that he did not petition the monarch to stage a CART race in
Morocco, but he indicated his immediate priorities were to set
CART's 2001 schedule and to raise the level of awareness of
open-wheel racing in America, specifically the CART FedEx
Championship Series. ``Those are the things we can do,'' he said.
``If we do that on site; I think if we do that in the marketplace,
that is going to help generate TV numbers. We have got to enlist
people. We have got to get them excited about what we are doing and
when you go to a Long Beach, you see what kind of excitement can be
generated . . . But I think the big thing is taking our drivers,
getting them out into the marketplace, making them more well known
than they already may be in different venues; really merchandising
the sport. I think if we do that, and we do it correctly, that
starts to drive a lot of these other issues that are problems for
us.'' . . . Helio Castroneves delivered car owner Roger Penske his
101st victory when he scored the first of his CART driving career
in last weekend's Tenneco Automotive Grand Prix in Detroit. The
excitable Brazilian driver celebrated in an unusual manner when he
stopped his Marlboro Team Penske Honda/Reynard on the front
straightaway of the Belle Isle circuit, unbuckled himself, and
stirred up the crowd when he jumped up on the fence in front of the
grandstands. ``Team Penske gave me the opportunity this year to
achieve my dream,'' said Castroneves, who became the seventh
different winner in seven CART races this season. ``Today
everything was going in the right direction.'' After the race,
Castroneves visited injured colleague Tony Kanaan, who suffered a
fractured arm and ribs after a wall crash last Saturday morning.
Castroneves said Kanaan was in good spirits when he offered the
following suggestion: ``Hey, man, should I stay here a little bit
and fix your nose?'' . . . Eddie Cheever vaulted into the points
lead of the Northern Light Indy Racing League standings after his
victory last weekend in the Radisson 200 at Pikes Peak (Colo.)
International Raceway. Cheever, who has finished all five races
this season while leading the most laps of any IRL driver (1,207),
delivered the first victory for the Nissan Infiniti engine program,
ending a 33-race drought. ``Today I had an advantage and that
advantage was the powerplant in the back of my car,'' said Cheever,
whose victory gave him an 8-point lead over Buddy Lazier, 176-168,
in the standings.
</P>
</TEXT>
