<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADISON IS BUILDING TRUST WITH DOLPHINS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Gene Burrough, an agent for 30 years who has
represented football stars such as Billy Sims, Deion Sanders, Jim
McMahon, Hugh Douglas, and LeRoy Butler, thinks the media missed
the boat regarding the recent signing of Dolphins cornerback Sam
Madison to an eight-year, $54 million deal with an $11 million
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the enormous amount that was the story, but the
way the contract was structured _ Madison put $7 million of the
bonus into a trust that could easily expand to more than $20
million (based on a 20 percent return) by the end of the eight-year
deal. The kickers are that the Dolphins have final approval on
which money manager Madison chooses and they can recover part of
the bonus if Madison somehow defaults on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it looks like a deal that may change the way
agents and football teams do business. NFL teams love the concept,
Madison and Burrough do as well, but the National Football League
Players' Association isn't going to like it, and when it finally
looks over the fine print, it will likely advise agents not to
engage in this type of deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly,'' said NFLPA spokesman Carl Francis, ``we haven't
been able to review the contract in its entirety yet. At that point
we'll be able to offer a clear opinion on how we feel about it. It
does appear to be a very unique deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Lions would have benefited if they had signed Barry
Sanders to such a deal. They had gone to great lengths to recoup
part of his bonus even though language in most NFL contracts
requires the player give back a prorated portion of the bonus in
case of voluntary retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have had a tougher time trying to recover $1.8
million of cornerback Dale Carter's $7.8 million bonus. Carter was
suspended by the NFL for a year for violating the league's
substance abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   Those on the players' side feel that this type of contract might
be taking away basic rights the union has fought for. In fact,
there's some question as to whether the contract takes away
Madison's right to a second opinion on a medical situation and his
ability to grieve a team fine or disciplinary action. The contract
extends four years beyond the current basic agreement and two years
after the contract can be amortized.
</P>
<P>
   Just what did Burrough and the Dolphins do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Sam and I said, `Is $11 million enough to live on?'
He said, `Of course it is,' so I said, `Why not put most of it in a
trust? The numbers say he could have at least $20 million
guaranteed in eight years. The team is protected and Sam's future
is protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in football could a deal like this be possible because the
contracts are not guaranteed. The Red Sox recently tried to find a
loophole to get out of the final 1 1/2 years of John Valentin's
contract. The Red Sox were willing to say that Valentin followed
the wrong procedure in having his surgery performed, thus
nullifying the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If he played football, Valentin would have been long gone,
similar to what the Patriots did to Bruce Armstrong. In football,
all that's guaranteed is the signing bonus, providing the player
doesn't quit prematurely or suffer an off-field injury or commit a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dolphins do not have a hand in picking the actual
investment funds, they would certainly be able to step in if the
investments were too risky. Burrough said the Dolphins will also
receive monthly statements on how Madison's money is doing.
</P>
<P>
   While the deal sounds obtrusive and could never fly in other
sports, the team and the player appear quite content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not rocket science,'' said Burrough, who works out of
Jacksonville, Fla. ``We have a player who is willing to take part
in this and apply sound money management skills to protect him in
the future. I'm tired of kids winding up broke at the end of their
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, you don't have to be Leigh Steinberg to come up with a
good deal. I didn't want Sam to sign one of those phony deals where
there was a big total but the player had little chance of seeing
the money at the end of the contract. I know based on a 20 percent
return, that Sam will have $20 million at the end of the contract
and he can make $42 million at the end of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Madison to earn a $385,000 base salary this
season, $2.7 million next year, $4.3 million in 2002 and then
salaries of $4.3 million, $5.3 million, $6.3 million, $6.7 million,
$7.015 million, and $7.4 million. This will likely be one of those
deals that is reworked after the third year because the cap number
will be too high. But even when it is, the new deal will come with
a new signing bonus and Burrough will recommend the same type of
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Burrough understands the management side of the game. He was the
general manager for the USFL Houston Gamblers and New Jersey
Generals and was instrumental in bringing Jim Kelly to the USFL. He
has seen athletes sign what he considers the ``most ridiculous''
deals over the years and get taken. He said he tried to structure
deals differently in the past, but ``I think I just made them too
complicated and they didn't work. When the Dolphins suggested I
come up with something different that would protect the team and
the player, I came up with the trust. It seems to work well for
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have done one of those stupid deals and gotten the big
numbers with big headlines, but those deals don't involve real
money. This is real money. Eight years from now, Sam will be a very
wealthy young man,'' said Burrough.
</P>
<P>
   Madison will be the second highest-paid cornerback in the league
behind Ty Law, but ``we weren't interested in making Sam the
highest paid cornerback. We wanted to make him the best paid
cornerback,'' Burrough said.
</P>
<P>
   This has apparently ensured that. As it has ensured Wayne
Huizenga that Madison's $11 million bonus will be invested well and
money will be there in case Madison decides to play a pickup
basketball game and permanently injures himself, ending his career.
</P>
<P>
   Is the deal unique?
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh-based agent Ralph Cindrich set up a ``Rabbi trust''
in 1985 for Bill Fralic, investing a certain amount of money that
would pay Fralic $150,000 the rest of his life. Other agents have
set up trusts and annuities for their clients, but this may be one
of the first deals in which the team actually has hands-on access
to the money.
</P>
<P>
   While some agents say the NFLPA will have no standing to object
to this type of arrangement, it could certainly put out an advisory
to agents that it frowns upon such deals and then discipline agents
who break the union's guidelines. The NFLPA has gotten tougher with
how its agents do business. It has gone after Tank Black for his
alleged role in bilking clients out of millions, and it has
suspended and fined other agents for breaking the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The final word has not been spoken on this unique arrangement,
hailed as innovative and exciting by some, dangerous by others.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Patriots didn't have to worry about Madison. They
took Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are going to score a financial bonanza _ $80
million to $100 million _ when they offer their new stadium up for
naming rights whether it's Monster.com or Gillette or John Hancock
or Fleet. In cities such as Denver and Green Bay, where new
stadiums and renovations are in the works and where the public
outlay is far greater than in New England, the naming rights fee
will go directly back to the city and state. Might this be a
negotiable point in cities like Boston, where there's concern about
the public outlay? Obviously teams look forward to naming rights to
defer their own stadium costs, but if there's a sharing of those
naming fees it may be a gesture of goodwill by the team and, in
some cases, a deal-maker. Nonetheless, imagine a $295 million
renovation of Lambeau Field resulting in the remodeled facility
being known as the Oscar Mayer Bowl. The Packers have certainly
tried to put off the inevitable, but defraying costs to the
taxpayers is winning out . . . The next couple of years will be a
true indication of whether Bill Belichick made the right choice
during that terribly awkward press conference last winter when he
informed the world that he was resigning as coach of the New York
Jets. Citing reasons of uncertainty about the new ownership and the
many years of being under Bill Parcells's watch and thumb,
Belichick left and created a sticky mess that was ultimately
resolved by the Patriots giving up a No. 1 draft pick to the Jets
as compensation. The Jets went with Al Groh, who is also a terrific
defensive coach, and who is taking on basically what Pete Carroll
had to take on in New England _ replacing Parcells. The one
difference, and it's a huge one, is that Groh is taking over a team
following a disappointing 8-8 season, not after a team went to the
Super Bowl. He is taking over a team that had four No. 1 draft
picks, though granted, he did lose one of the best players in the
game, Keyshawn Johnson, to do so. The ownership was resolved in
what appears to be the best scenario possible _ Woody Johnson, like
Bob Kraft, is a lifelong fan of his team and one who has deep
pockets and can build a winner. What we'll find out in the next
couple of years is which team is better off. For the immediate
future, however, the Jets appear ahead of the game. Quarterback
Vinny Testaverde is returning from a nasty injury to his Achilles'
tendon, the Jets have a star running back in Curtis Martin, and
Parcells is still running the operation. On the negative side,
Belichick is gone and so are his innovative defenses . . . Eagles
owner Jeffrey Lurie is having the same problem with Philadelphia
that John Harrington and Kraft had in Boston. Lurie is willing to
fork up more than $300 million for a new facility in downtown
Philly as part of a two-stadium complex with the Phillies, but the
deal has gotten mired in all sorts of political mumbo-jumbo. Lurie,
a Newton native, has not yet threatened he'll leave Philly, but
that's sure to come soon . . . Speaking of stadium sites, the
Weymouth Naval Air Station would have been a great site for the
Patriots and we must wonder whether the Red Sox will ever consider
it if talks with Boston fall apart. With gobs of space and one of
the biggest malls in America in the works, it appears to be a
natural place for a ballpark and a hotel or two . . . The feel good
number of the week: Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp shot a
108 at the NFL Cadillac Golf Classic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Redskins will pay their players more than $100 million
this season in pursuit of the Super Bowl (and still somehow stay
under the $62.2 million salary cap), they are about to undergo a
series of cuts, position by position, to whittle the numbers a tad.
The Redskins probably won't do a lot of earth-shattering things,
but look for a player or two of decent value to become available .
. . With 14 offensive linemen, the Patriots feel they're all set
and the likelihood that Armstrong will be a part of the team
appears slimmer. They must be seeing something the rest of us
don't. The Patriots, in fact, will likely need to cut some
candidates before training camp. Ed Ellis, who had so many problems
in Barcelona before being asked to leave, may be one of the
casualties . . . It is now clear that ``Monday Night Football'' is
scared to death of Vince McMahon and the WWF. The wrestling
organization has taken viewers away from MNF the past few years to
the point where the program suffered its lowest ratings ever last
season. When the ratings drop, the TV execs begin to do things that
look more and more like their successful competition. The WWF can
be funny, so now MNF will be funny with comedian Dennis Miller as
the third man in the booth. The WWF attracts male-dominated
audiences with young women, so MNF went from 46-year-old Lesley
Visser to 26-year-old Melissa Stark as a sideline reporter. It's
just not football at MNF anymore, but ``sports entertainment,'' a
concept that has made McMahon a very wealthy man . . . Former
Patriot Willie Clay is still waiting for a call to return to the
playing field. With a few teams, including the Patriots, in need of
an experienced free safety, he'll likely work soon. For now, Clay
is running his construction company in Atlanta while keeping in
shape for the call . . . Tony Agnone said client Sam Gash has
rejected offers to play for the Jets and Giants. ``Sam's back home
in North Carolina and he's going to sit and wait for a longer-term
spot. He doesn't want a deal where he's gone after a year. There
have been five or six teams (none of which are the Patriots)
interested all along and we'll wait and see. We know there will be
injuries and Sam might get a situation he likes then. If it comes
down to a one-year deal, then Sam will then make a decision based
on what he thinks would be right for him.'' . . . Former Patriots
running back/punt and kick returner Dave Meggett has been cleared
of all charges stemming from a Toronto hotel incident involving a
call girl. Meggett, who has retired from football, is mulling two
coaching possibilities _ as an assistant with the Jets as part of
the NFL coaches internship program, or as a voluntary assistant at
his alma mater, Towson State. Meggett has earned his degree from
Towson and is now pursuing a master's degree . . . Defensive tackle
Gabe Wilkins would have been a nice fit for the Patriots, but the
former 49er is having knee surgery that will force him to sit out
the season . . . Former Giants running back Gary Brown has two
offers on the table and is expected to decide soon whether to
accept one or retire . . . Angelo Wright, who represents Sean
Dawkins, said he has told both the Jets and the Packers, the two
front-runners for the wide receiver's services, to outline their
contractual game plan soon. ``We just want a situation where if
it's only a one-year deal that the team will enter into
negotiations during the season for a longer-term deal.'' After
losing Johnson, the Jets appear to have the greatest need for the
former Colt and Seahawk, who caught 58 passes last season . . .
Former Patriots and Dolphins quarterback Scott Zolak has received
calls from five teams and expects to be in someone's camp . . .
Jimmy Johnson is enjoying retirement in the Florida Keys. He has
been back to the mainland a few times since he announced his
retirement, once for a birthday party . . . Most football
executives took the week off, therefore there wasn't much activity
around the league, although the Tennessee Titans made it known
they'll be pursuing Reggie White this week. With Josh Evans
suspended by the league, the Titans have a need for a defensive
lineman, but why White, who retired and didn't play last year? The
Jaguars are already on record as saying they don't have an
interest, but that could change if the Tony Brackens contract
dispute gets uglier and Brackens decides to sit out . . . The NFLPA
is holding its rookie symposium Monday in San Diego, where it will
lecture players on drugs, sex, crime, life in the NFL, etc. These
are annual sessions, but given the enormous amount of trouble
players are getting into these days, the union is trying to get
tougher with its players on getting their act together and
listening to the message. One thing it did last week was send out
memos to agents asking them to continue to school their clients on
the importance of good citizenship.
</P>
</TEXT>
