<SLUG> BC-SAILING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM DOES IT FOR RESTLESS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By TONY CHAMBERLAIN 
c.2000 The Boston Globe 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ About noon last Sunday, Bermuda Race watchers thought
the unlikely was about to occur _ a record in the 42d biennial
Newport-Bermuda Race.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh southwesterly winds _ pumping up on a weather system known
in the summer as a Bermuda high _ blew for two days and nights
between 17 and 25 knots, according to race spokesman Talbot Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Maxi boat Sayonara _ with Chris Dickson at the helm and a rock
star crew _ was just 121 miles from the finish at St. David's
Light, with George Coumantaros's Boomerang and James Dolan's
Sagamore just astern and within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   At an average speed of 12.23 knots, Sayonara and the other two
Maxis were well ahead of the record pace for this bluewater classic
set in 1996 by Boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   But through the day Sunday, hearts were sinking as fast as the
anemometer needle. The Bermuda High _ sitting on top of the island
_ had snuffed out all but a trace breeze of less than 5 knots from
the north, and the only hope for a record finish was a low-pressure
system moving slowly off the Annapolis coast.
</P>
<P>
   Racers hoped the low might nudge the high pressure lock far
enough east to allow some fresh breeze in for a record finish.
Alas, no such luck for the Maxis, but the sudden wind drop from 16
knots to light vapors in the last 100 miles of the race set up a
great finish for one of the smallest and unlikeliest yachts in the
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Crawford from Maryland, sailing Restless _ his 35-year-old
Rhodes/Pearson 41, the highest handicap in the 176-boat fleet _ was
able to make up time as the leaders stalled. After the handicap
correction, Restless won the Bermuda Lighthouse Trophy as the
overall winner.
</P>
<P>
   What made Crawford's victory even sweeter was that a
family-owned fiberglass boat with a crew of old friends beat some
of the fastest carbon-fiber boats and top professional sailors in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   America's Cup sailors Dickson, Kenny Read, Peter Isler, Moose
McClintock, and Brad Butterworth were but a few of the star-studded
flotilla that left Newport midday Friday and kept up a torrid pace
across the Gulf Stream, only to have the wind stall out in the last
100 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Restless and skipper Crawford _ who inherited the
immaculate 35-year-old sloop from his inlaws 13 years ago _ were
blind-luck winners. For the first 24 hours, Restless covered 208
miles for an average speed of 8.6 knots.
</P>
<P>
   But Crawford _ a lifelong sailor who has made a circumnavigation
of the world by sail _ made several correct calls, positioning
Restless well enough in the Gulf Stream to take advantage of the
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As the wind died among the leaders, Restless used the current to
continue moving ahead and, as one of the smallest and unlikeliest
boats in the fleet, she was close enough to win the overall trophy
on corrected time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good handicap,'' said Crawford at the docks of the
Royal Bermuda Yacht Squadron in Hamilton Tuesday, ``but I would
like to think this win came down to the skill of my crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Line honors were also a bit of a surprise, as Sagamore ghosted
ahead of leader Sayonara Monday night to cross the St. David's
Lighthouse line on Day 3 in 23 hours 2 minutes 39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Sayonara finished 13 minutes back, with Blue Yankee third (Day
3, 23 hours 53 minutes 44 seconds). Course record-holder Boomerang
_ skippered by the 83-year-old Coumantaros in his 50th year of
yacht racing, came in fourth overall. It finished on Day 4 at 00
hours 3 minutes 59 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 in the evening light, sailors aboard Sayonara reported
they were about 45 miles from St. David Light and that the sea had
become ``mirror calm'' around them.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the cruiser fleet to cross the line was Zaraffa
owned and sailed by Skip Sheldon from Shelburne, Vt., who took the
gun on Day 4 at 00 hours 30 minutes 37 seconds, beating out Trader
_ sailed by Fred Detwiler from Grosse Point, Mich., by about 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In America's Cup developments, billionaire Craig McCaw
formalized his intention to back the OneWorld Challenge Syndicate,
one of two Seattle-based Cup challenges in a city that has never
sailed in the event.
</P>
<P>
   Though the formation of the syndicate has not been a well-kept
secret, McCaw formally announced his entrance into the 2002 Cup at
a luncheon at Seattle Yacht Club in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With a budget reported around $75 million, McCaw continues the
trend of the America's Cup being taken over by wealthy backers who
need little corporate sponsorship. This is actually a throwback to
the Cup's early days when names like Vanderbilt, Lipton, Adams, and
Sopwith dominated sailing's ultimate event. It was rekindled by
modern barons such as Alan Bond, Michael Fay, and Bill Koch, though
corporate fund-raising has been increasingly part of the Cup scene
for many less-well-heeled competitors. At age 50, McCaw is founder
of the satellite communications company, Teledesic, and is listed
among the world's wealthiest individuals.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's OneWorld Challenge also continues the plunder of New
Zealand's two-time winning team, which, at the end of the 2000 Cup
in Auckland, New Zealand, appeared unbeatable and perhaps a
favorite for several Cups in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Kiwi designer Laurie Davidson will head the OneWorld design
team, and Australian Peter Gilmour, who skippered for Japan in the
last Cup, will be director of sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Six other members of OneWorld are former Team New Zealand
members, including Richard Dodson, Matthew Mason, Craig Monk,
Jeremy Scantlebury, Andrew Taylor, and Pete Weymouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The America's Cup is a race that has been run with sailors
from throughout the world since the turn of the century,'' says Bob
Ratliffe, spokesman for OneWorld, putting forth the syndicate's
official line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another Seattle challenge has formed under the
Corinthian Yacht Club burgee, headed by Russell Belden. Called the
Seattle Challenge, Belden originally sought sponsorship from the
Seattle Yacht Club, though he is not a member. When the club failed
to commit to Belden, the Seattle Challenge joined forces with the
Corinthian Yacht Club. ``Seattle is a world-class city, very
capable of supporting two strong syndicates,'' Belden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
