<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INEXPLICABLE'S NOSE MAKES IT 
</HEADLINE>
 SWEEPSTAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ When the field is full of speed horses, it pays to
be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Jose Santos proved that Saturday, as he sat behind a hot
pace, then drove Inexplicable up from the middle of the pack to nip
Where's Taylor by a nose and win the 21st running of the $200,000
New Hampshire Sweepstakes at Rockingham Park.
</P>
<P>
   The race was marred when Haami, the 9-5 choice, apparently
fractured his left front knee approaching the far turn, was pulled
up by rider Robbie Davis, and taken from the track in a van. Haami
was eating, and being iced after the race, and the injury is not
considered life-threatening. However, his racing career is probably
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race went perfect for me,'' said Santos, who won the
Sweeps aboard Fourstars Allstar in 1993 and Statesmanship in '98.
``When that horse broke down on the backstretch, I got my horse in
pretty good position. But the horse in front of me (Where's Taylor)
kept on going in the stretch. My horse is a very nice horse. I
didn't know I'd won untill the announcer said my number. I thought
my horse felt very strong, but I never thought we'd set a track
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicable, the fourth choice at 7-2 ($9.80 to win), covered
the ``about'' distance of 1 1/8 miles over the extremely firm turf
course in 1:45, breaking the mark of 1:45 3/5 set by Kiri's Clown
in 1995. Distant Mirage and Aaron Gryder checked in a well-beaten
third, but this was a classic two-horse battle.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Taylor, who began his career at Rock, stalked the pace
and took over with a big move. It appeared the 5-2 second choice,
trained by Michael Stidham and based at Arlington Park, would draw
away, until Inexplicable came roaring up on the outside. Where's
Taylor battled to the wire, but simply lost the bob as the pair
flashed under the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race set up good for him,'' said C. J. Lanerie, who rode
Where's Taylor. ``When the horse broke down, everybody checked, and
he got a lead on the turn. We just got caught in the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   From the powerful New York stable of trainer Christophe Clement,
Inexplicable, a son of Miswaki, out of a Nureyev mare, is a
5-year-old who has run only 13 times. For the first seven races of
his career, he was a dirt sprinter, running in top company. But he
became a stakes horse when Clement switched him to the turf and
sent him long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finished very well,'' said Nicholas Bachalard, assistant to
Clement. ``There was a lot of speed in the race, and Jose kept him
off the pace. He just got up in time. This was his stakes debut. We
had hopes for him on the dirt, but we decided to switch him to the
grass. He's better on turf. We were concerned about the distance,
but he handled it well. We've had quite a few problems with him,
little ones, which is why we're still running him at age 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no current plans for him, but there are a lot of races
around. He's been doing very well. He's a very good horse, and a
very happy horse. He's sound. Santos rode a good race. He came on
at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Haami was most unfortunate. A 5-year-old owned by
the Shadwell Stable of Sheikh Hamdan, the Minister of Finance of
Dubai, Haami deserved the role of favorite off his fine record in
both Europe and the United States. He was headstrong, pulling Davis
up on the outside, and was laying second to frontruner Johnny
Dollar (who faded to sixth in the 10-horse field), when the injury
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a few bad steps, and jumped a little,'' said Davis.
``He went another 10 or 12 strides, but he had nothing. I eased up
on him, and I think he fractured something.''
</P>
<P>
   Distant Mirage won the Old Ironsides Stakes at Suffolk Downs
June 3, but this was a much tougher spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an eventful trip,'' said Gryder. ``We got squeezed at
the first turn, but we got behind the speed. Then he settled in and
ran a real good race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
